Class: Temporal Reference System. Definition: A temporal reference system, such as a temporal coordinate system (with an origin, direction, and scale), a calendar-clock combination, or a (possibly hierarchical) ordinal system.   This is a stub class, representing the set of all temporal reference systems.

Class: Temporal Reference System. Definition: Un sistema de referencia temporal, tal como un sistema de coordenadas temporales (con un origen, una dirección y una escala), una combinación calendario-reloj, o un sistema ordinal (posiblemente jerárquico).         Esta clase comodín representa el conjunto de todos los sistemas de referencia temporal.

Class: sistema de referencia temporal. Definition: A temporal reference system, such as a temporal coordinate system (with an origin, direction, and scale), a calendar-clock combination, or a (possibly hierarchical) ordinal system.   This is a stub class, representing the set of all temporal reference systems.

Class: sistema de referencia temporal. Definition: Un sistema de referencia temporal, tal como un sistema de coordenadas temporales (con un origen, una dirección y una escala), una combinación calendario-reloj, o un sistema ordinal (posiblemente jerárquico).         Esta clase comodín representa el conjunto de todos los sistemas de referencia temporal.
Class: Temporal Duration. Definition: Time extent; duration of a time interval separate from its particular start position
Class: Temporal_Entity. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: Temporal Position. Definition: A position on a time-line
Class: Temporal Unit. Definition: A standard duration, which provides a scale factor for a time extent, or the granularity or precision for a time position.
Class: Time Position. Definition: A temporal position described using either a (nominal) value from an ordinal reference system, or a (numeric) value in a temporal coordinate system.

Class: Time Zone. Definition: A Time Zone specifies the amount by which the local time is offset from UTC.    A time zone is usually denoted geographically (e.g. Australian Eastern Daylight Time), with a constant value in a given region.  The region where it applies and the offset from UTC are specified by a locally recognised governing authority.
Class: day of week. Definition: The day of week, whose value is a member of the class time:DayOfWeek
Class: in time zone. Definition: The time zone for clock elements in the temporal position
Class: Observation Collection. Definition: An Observation Collection has at least one member, and may have one of any of the other seven properties mentioned in restrictions.

Class: Organization. Definition: Represents a collection of people organized together into a community or other social, commercial or political structure. The group has some common purpose or reason for existence which goes beyond the set of people belonging to it and can act as an Agent. Organizations are often decomposed into hierarchical structures.

Class: Organizational Unit. Definition: An Organization such as a department or support unit which is part of some larger Organization and only has full recognition within the context of that Organization. In particular the unit would not be regarded as a legal entity in its own right.
Class: Organizational Unit. Definition: Usage: Units can be large and complex containing other Units.
Class: Actuatable Property. Definition: An actuatable quality (property, characteristic) of a FeatureOfInterest.
Class: Actuation. Definition: An Actuation carries out an (Actuation) Procedure to change the state of the world using an Actuator.
Class: Actuator. Definition: A device that is used by, or implements, an (Actuation) Procedure that changes the state of the world.

Class: Feature Of Interest. Definition: The thing whose property is being estimated or calculated in the course of an Observation to arrive at a Result or whose property is being manipulated by an Actuator, or which is being sampled or transformed in an act of Sampling.
Class: Observable Property. Definition: An observable quality (property, characteristic) of a FeatureOfInterest.

Class: Observation. Definition: Act of carrying out an (Observation) Procedure to estimate or calculate a value of a property of a FeatureOfInterest. Links to a Sensor to describe what made the Observation and how; links to an ObservableProperty to describe what the result is an estimate of, and to a FeatureOfInterest to detail what that property was associated with.
Class: Platform. Definition: A Platform is an entity that hosts other entities, particularly Sensors, Actuators, Samplers, and other Platforms.

Class: Procedure. Definition: A workflow, protocol, plan, algorithm, or computational method specifying how to make an Observation, create a Sample, or make a change to the state of the world (via an Actuator). A Procedure is re-usable, and might be involved in many Observations, Samplings, or Actuations. It explains the steps to be carried out to arrive at reproducible results.
Class: Result. Definition: The Result of an Observation, Actuation, or act of Sampling. To store an observation's simple result value one can use the hasSimpleResult property.
Class: Sample. Definition: A Sample is the result from an act of Sampling.
Class: Sample. Definition: Feature which is intended to be representative of a FeatureOfInterest on which Observations may be made.
Class: Sample. Definition: Physical samples are sometimes known as 'specimens'.

Class: Sample. Definition: Samples are artifacts of an observational strategy, and have no significant function outside of their role in the observation process. The characteristics of the samples themselves are of little interest, except perhaps to the manager of a sampling campaign.  A Sample is intended to sample some FatureOfInterest, so there is an expectation of at least one isSampleOf property. However, in some cases the identity, and even the exact type, of the sampled feature may not be known when observations are made using the sampling features.
Class: Sampler. Definition: A device that is used by, or implements, a Sampling Procedure to create or transform one or more samples.
Class: Sampling. Definition: An act of Sampling carries out a sampling Procedure to create or transform one or more samples.

Class: Sensor. Definition: Device, agent (including humans), or software (simulation) involved in, or implementing, a Procedure. Sensors respond to a stimulus, e.g., a change in the environment, or input data composed from the results of prior Observations, and generate a Result. Sensors can be hosted by Platforms.
Class: Relationship Nature. Definition: Nature of a relationship (between samples) - Members of this class indicate the nature of a relationship between two samples.
Class: Sample Relationship. Definition: Members of this class represent a relationship between a sample and another.
Class: Condition. Definition: Used to specify ranges for qualities that act as Condition on a Systems' operation.
Class: Deployment. Definition: Describes the Deployment of one or more Systems for a particular purpose. Deployment may be done on a Platform.
Class: Input. Definition: Any information that is provided to a Procedure for its use.
Class: Output. Definition: Any information that is reported from a Procedure.
Class: Oversampling Rate. Definition: Specifies the number of sensor measurements used internally to generate one sensor output result. (Oversampling rate = OSR)
Class: Property. Definition: A quality of an entity. An aspect of an entity that is intrinsic to and cannot exist without the entity.

Class: Stimulus. Definition: An event in the real world that 'triggers' the Sensor. The properties associated to the Stimulus may be different to the eventual observed ObservableProperty. It is the event, not the object, that triggers the Sensor.
Class: System. Definition: System is a unit of abstraction for pieces of infrastructure that implement Procedures. A System may have components, its subsystems, which are other systems.

Class: Accuracy. Definition: The closeness of agreement between the Result of an Observation (resp. The command of an Actuation) and the true value of the observed ObservableProperty (resp. Of the acted on ActuableProperty) under the defined Conditions.
Class: Actuation Range. Definition: The range of property values that can be the Result of an Actuation under the defined Conditions.
Class: Battery Lifetime. Definition: Total useful life of a System's battery in the specified Conditions.

Class: Detection Limit. Definition: An observed value for which the probability of falsely claiming the absence of a component in a material is beta, given a probability alpha of falsely claiming its presence.

Class: Drift. Definition: As a Sensor Property: a continuous or incremental change in the reported values of Observations over time for an unchanging Property under the defined Conditions. As an Actuator Property: a continuous or incremental change in the true value of the acted on ActuableProperty over time for an unchanging command under the defined Conditions.
Class: Frequency. Definition: The smallest possible time between one Observation, Actuation, or Sampling and the next, under the defined Conditions.
Class: Latency. Definition: The time between a command for an Observation and the Sensor providing a Result, under the defined Conditions.
Class: Maintenance Schdule. Definition: Schedule of maintenance for a System in the specified Conditions.
Class: Measurement Range. Definition: The set of values that the Sensor can return as the Result of an Observation under the defined Conditions with the defined system properties.
Class: Operating Power Range. Definition: Power range in which System is expected to operate in the specified.

Class: Operating Property. Definition: An identifiable characteristic that represents how the System operates under the specified Conditions. May describe power ranges, power sources, standard configurations, attachments and the like.

Class: Operating Range. Definition: "Describes normal OperatingProperties of a System under some specified Conditions. For example, to the power requirement or maintenance schedule of a System under a specified temperature range. In the absence of OperatingProperties, it simply describes the Conditions in which a System is expected to operate."

Class: Precision. Definition: As a sensor capability: The closeness of agreement between replicate Observations on an unchanged or similar quality value: i.e., a measure of a Sensor's ability to consistently reproduce an Observation, under the defined Conditions.

Class: Resolution. Definition: As an actuator capability: The closeness of agreement between replicate Actuations for an unchanged or similar command: i.e., a measure of an Actuator's ability to consistently reproduce an Actuations, under the defined Conditions.

Class: Response Time. Definition: As a Sensor Property: the time between a (step) change in the value of an observed ObservableProperty and a Sensor (possibly with specified error) 'settling' on an observed value, under the defined Conditions.

Class: Selectivity. Definition: As an Actuator Property: the time between a (step) change in the command of an Actuator and the 'settling' of the value of the acted on ActuatableProperty, under the defined Conditions.

Class: Sensitivity. Definition: As a Sensor Property: Sensitivity is the quotient of the change in a Result of Observations and the corresponding change in a value of an ObservableProperty being observed, under the defined Conditions.

Class: Survival Property. Definition: An identifiable characteristic that represents the extent of the System's useful life under the specified Conditions. May describe for example total battery life or number of recharges, or, for Sensors that are used only a fixed number of times, the number of Observations that can be made before the sensing capability is depleted.

Class: Survival Range. Definition: "Describes SurvivalProperties of a System under some specified Conditions. For example, the lifetime of a System under a specified temperature range. In the absence of SurvivalProperties, simply describes the Conditions a System can be exposed to without damage. For example, the temperature range a System can withstand before being considered damaged."

Class: System Capability. Definition: Describes normal measurement, actuation, sampling properties such as accuracy, range, precision, etc. Of a System under some specified Conditions such as temperature range. The capabilities specified here are those that affect the primary purpose of the System, while those in OperatingRange represent the system's normal operating environment, including Conditions that don't affect the Observations or the Actuations.

Class: System Lifetime. Definition: The System continues to operate as defined using SystemCapability. If, however, the SurvivalRange is violated, the System is 'damaged' and SystemCapability specifications may no longer hold.

Class: System Property. Definition: An identifiable and observable characteristic that represents the system's ability to operate its primary purpose: a sensor to make Observations, an Actuator to make Actuations, or a Sampler to make Sampling.
Class: Application. Definition: A way in which something can be used for a particular purpose.

Class: Cloud Lobe. Definition: Cloud refers to a network of remote servers that store, manage, and process data and applications, providing on-demand access and scalable computing resources over the internet.  The Cloud lobe of the Digital Reference ontology models AH Local Cloud, Communication Technology, Data Format and Model, Device, and Documentation Document. It also maps the topics of Information Model, Local Network, Method, SoA Property, Software and Software System, system Documentation and System of Systems. It represents the notion of  Service, Service Documentation, Service-Oriented Architecture and Architecture Protocols.
Class: Cloud Lobe. Definition: Lobe owner: Jerker Delsing
Class: Geographical Location. Definition: Name of country or region
Class: IDM. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: Organization. Definition: No definition provided.

Class: Organization Lobe. Definition: The Organization Lobe refers to the structural and managerial aspects such as organizational structure, roles and responsibilities, efficient coordination and collaboration among various stakeholders within the semiconductor supply chains.
Class: Organization Lobe. Definition: Lobe owner: Marta Bonik
Class: OSAT. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: Planning Lobe. Definition: Lobe owner: Hans Ehm

Class: Planning Lobe. Definition: The Planning Lobe is about making strategic decisions and creating comprehensive plans to ensure the efficient and effective flow of materials, products, and information throughout the manufacturing and distribution process. In includes information about marketing and sales demans, demand march, aggregated capacity, capacity bottlenecks, orders and customers.

Class: Power Lobe. Definition: Power refers to the electrical energy consumed or dissipated by electronic devices or components during their operation, and is a crucial consideration for efficiency and performance optimization.  The Power lobe models the Amplication Switching Device, Control Method, Device Configuration and Element, Document, Entity, and Gate Driver. It also represents the notions of Industrial Sector, Information Object, Operation Mode, Process, Process Input and Output. It maps the topics of Product, Resistance, SiC MOSFET, switcher, and Voltage.
Class: Power Lobe. Definition: Lobe owner: Hans Ehm

Class: Process Lobe. Definition: Process refers to a series of interconnected and sequential actions, steps, or operations designed to achieve a specific outcome or goal within a system or organization.  The Process lobe of the Digital Reference ontology represents the topics of Agent, Business Process Flow, Function and Function Object. It also maps the notions of Goal, Input, Model and Model Element, Output, Screen, and Value-added Chain Diagram.
Class: Process Lobe. Definition: Lobe owner: Hans Ehm

Class: Product Lobe. Definition: A product is a tangible or intangible item or service that is created, manufactured, or offered to fulfill a need or desire of customers.  The Product Lobe maps the notions of Customer Part Number Specification, Design Target, Integration Level, Main Power Device Type, Motor Type and Organization. It also models Packing Type, Planning Element, Price Indication, Product, Qualification, Semiconductor Product Status, Solution, and Topology.
Class: Product Lobe. Definition: Lobe owner: Marta Bonik
Class: Public Holiday. Definition: Special period of time when some processes may not take place or some constrains may occure

Class: Semiconductor Development Lobe. Definition: Semiconductor development refers to the process of researching, designing, and creating semiconductor devices to meet technological advancements and industry demands.  The Semiconductor Development lobe of the Digital Reference models the Current Work In Progress, Cycle Time and Delivery Commitment, EPA, Equipment and Equipent Group, and Event Calendar. It reprensents the notions of Mask, Material Transfer Matrix, Operation, Operator, Owner, Planning Work Center, Plant,  and Process. It also maps the topics of Product Level, Target Revenue and Service Level, Technology, Time Constraints, Tool, and Workshop.
Class: Semiconductor Development Lobe. Definition: Lobe owner: Hans Ehm
Class: Semiconductor Production Lobe. Definition: Lobe owner: Philipp Ulrich

Class: Semiconductor Production Lobe. Definition: Semiconductor production refers to the manufacturing process of creating integrated circuits and other semiconductor devices by deposing, patterning, and doping various materials on a substrate to form electronic components.  The Semiconductor Production lobe represents the notions of Bottleneck, Capacity, Demand Snapshot, Fabrication, Furnace Process, Lot, Lot Event and Size. It also maps the topics of Physical Resource, Priority Class, Product, Production Request, Purge, Release Plan, and Robot. It models Route, Shift, Simulation Part and Route, Supply Chain, Target Costs and Work In Progress Station.

Class: Sensor Lobe. Definition: A sensor is a device or component that detects and measures physical, chemical or environmental parameters and converts them into electrical signals for futher analysis or use.  The Sensor lobes models the notion of a System and its Deployment. It maps the topics of Actuation, Feature of Interest, Input, Mounting Style, Observation and Observation Collection, and  Output. It also represents Platform, Procedure, Property, Relationship Nature, Result, Sample Relationship, Sampling, Sensing Type, and Stimulus.
Class: Sensor Lobe. Definition: Lobe owner: Marta Bonik
Class: SiFo. Definition: No definition provided.

Class: Supply Chain Lobe. Definition: Supply chain refers to a network of interconnected organizations, activities, resources, and technologies involved in the production, distribution, and delivery of goods or services from the source to end consumer.  The Supply Chain lobe models the Aggregated Capacity Group.   It represents the notions of Action, Allocated Available To Promise, Allocation, Available To Promise, Confirmation, Capacity Bottleneck, Contact Person Data, Location, Marketing Demand, nEWs, Offer, Open Oder and Open Order Book.  It depicts the Order and its Change Request, Confirmation, Line Item, Reschedule, Schedule Line.  It represents the General Customers, the notion of Customer and its Data, Logistics Management Representative, Plant, Plant Data. It also maps the topics of Prioritized Demand and Orders, Products, Promise, Sales Supplier, Seller, Supplier and its Data, Supply, Supply Demand Match and Picture, Target Allocation, Transfer Action, and User Action.
Class: Supply Chain Lobe. Definition: Lobe owner: Philipp Ulrich

Class: Sustainability Lobe. Definition: Sustainability refers to the practice of meeting present needs without compromising the ability of future generations to meet their own needs, balancing environmental, social, and economic considerations.  This lobes models Application.
Class: Sustainability Lobe. Definition: Lobe owner: Philipp Ulrich

Class: System Lobe. Definition: A system is a collection of interconnected components or elements that work together to perform a specific function or achieve a particular objective.  This lobe of the Digital Reference models the I 4.0 Component, the Asset it represents, the Admin Shell and its differents Views, Standard and Standard Organization. It also represents the notions of Date, Dimension, Measures, Semantic Expresison and Version.
Class: System Lobe. Definition: Lobe owner: Marta Bonik

Class: Time Lobe. Definition: Time refers to a measurable dimension in which events occur sequentially and can be used to qualify the duration between occurences.  This lobe of the digital reference represents the topics of Temporal Duration, Position and Reference Position, the Time Zone, Months and Days of the week.
Class: Time Lobe. Definition: Lobe owner: Philipp Ulrich

Class: Wired Communication Lobe. Definition: Wired communication refers to the transmission of data or signals through physical connections such as cables or wires.  This lobe represents the units of technical data transfer, product lifecycle phase, standard unit and vocabulary. It models Fieldbus and its 7 OSI layers, ISA-95, IT system and vendor, the service-oriented architecture and the standardization organisation.

Class: Arrowhead Core Component. Definition: Software system, that belongs to the "standard" components offered by Arrowhead framework. Arrowhead core systems can occur once in each Arrowhead Local Cloud. Arriwhead Core Systems can be distinguished in Arrowhead Mandatory Core Systems and Automation supporting systems. Mandatory core systems must exist in each Arrowhead Local Cloud, Automation supporting systems can occur in an Arrowhead Local Cloud.

Class: AH Mandatory Core Service IDD. Definition: Class of all Interface Design Descriptions (IDDs) of mandatory Arrowwhead core services. While the class AH_mandatory_core_service contains the mandatory core services only as instances, this class contains classes of the IDDs of each single mandatory core service as subclasses (not only as instances). Since each AH Local Cloud runs one instance of each mandatory core service, each of these services has to be documented by an AH service documentation, i.e. at least by a SD and a IDD. So the IDD is an individual document for each mandatory core service in each single Local Cloud. Hence, all IDDs of a certain mandatory core service will be individuals of the corresponding IDD class.

Class: AH Service Documentation Document. Definition: Document belonging to the documentation of an Arrowhead Service. There are four types of documents for Arrowhead service documentations: - Service Description - Interface Design Description - Communication Profile - Semantic Profile. The central documents are IDDs. They document the implementation of a certain service based on a certain communication technology (communication, encoding, data format) and a certain information model. The Service Description contains a more general description of the service, without the link to a specific communication technology or information model. Communication Profiles and Semantic Profiles are optional documents for a service documentation. They can be seen as modules of an IDD, since they can describe the communication technolopgy and the information model of a service implementation as external documents. If they exist, the IDD refers to them instead of declaring these contents by themselfes. That is, CP and SP are useful if different service implementations use the same CP and SP - then their IDDs can refer to one and the same CP or SP document.

Class: System Web Application Description WADL. Definition: Description of an Arrowhead compliant software system in terms of the Web Application Description Language WADL. The Web Application Description Language (WADL) is a machine-readable XML description of HTTP-based web services. WADL models the resources provided by a service and the relationships between them. WADL is intended to simplify the reuse of web services that are based on the existing HTTP architecture of the Web. It is platform and language independent and aims to promote reuse of applications beyond the basic use in a web browser. WADL is the REST equivalent of SOAP's Web Services Description Language (WSDL), which can also be used to describe REST web services. Sources: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_Application_Description_Language Sun Microsystems (31 August 2009). "Web Application Description Language: W3C Member Submission 31 August 2009". Class: Digital Factory System. Definition: The term "Digital Factory" is used in different meanings today and should hence not longer be used. It should be replaced by more specific terms like "Digital Factory Planning system" or "Digital Factory Twin". Originally, Digital Factory referred to software tools for computer-aided planning, design, engineering and simulation of production, manufacturing, or assembly systems. These tools supplemented CAD-based tools for factory layout planning and tools for computer-aided tools for production engineering (work plan preparation, production process planning) and were glued together with them to PLM software suites. As today even CAD-based layout planning and process planning tools are "digital" and refer to the factory, the terms "Digital Factory tool" and "Production Engineering tool" more and more converge. At the same time, automation vendors start to use the concept "Digital Factory" to address online monitoring and control tools for production systems. In this meaning, the term is a synonym for "Digital Factory Twin" or "Digital Twin of a Factory". The important difference between these two meanings is the phase in the life cycle in which the tool is used: Manufacturing Planning / Eingineering is conducted mainly in the first two lifecycle phases in which the product (type, class) is created, designed, and engineered, as well as the corresponding production system. The online monitoring and control is conducted during the third phase, in which the product individuals are produced on the existing production system. Hartwig Baumgaertel, 2018-11-12

Class: Fieldbus Communication Profile Family. Definition: A field bus is a bus system that connects field devices such as sensors and actuators in a plant for the purpose of communication with an automation device. If several communication participants send their messages over the same line, then it must be specified who (identifier) says what (measured value, command) and when (initiative). There are standardized protocols for this. The first generation of fieldbus technology was developed in the 1980s to replace the parallel wiring of binary signals and analog signal transmission that had been common until then with digital transmission technology. Today, many different fieldbus systems with different characteristics are established on the market. Since 1999, fieldbuses have been standardized worldwide in the IEC 61158 standard (Digital data communication for measurement and control - Fieldbus for use in industrial control systems) and by the IEC 61784 standard. The second generation of fieldbus technology is based on real-time Ethernet (Industrial Ethernet).  A fieldbus defines a complete protocol stack over the 7 layers of the OSI layer model. If necessary, not all layers are occupied.  Example for first generation fieldbus is Profibus, Example for second generation fieldbus is ProfiNet.
Class: Fieldbus Communication Profile Family. Definition: Beispiel für Feldbus der ersten Generation ist Profibus, Beispiel für Feldbus der zweiten Generation ist ProfiNet.

Class: Fieldbus Communication Profile Family. Definition: Ein Feldbus ist ein Bussystem, das in einer Anlage Feldgeräte wie Messfühler (Sensoren) und Stellglieder (Aktoren) zwecks Kommunikation mit einem Automatisierungsgerät verbindet. Wenn mehrere Kommunikationsteilnehmer ihre Nachrichten über dieselbe Leitung senden, dann muss festgelegt sein, wer (Kennung) was (Messwert, Befehl) wann (Initiative) sagt. Hierfür gibt es normierte Protokolle. Die erste Generation der Feldbustechnik wurde in den 1980er Jahren entwickelt, um die bis dahin übliche Parallelverdrahtung binärer Signale sowie die analoge Signalübertragung durch digitale Übertragungstechnik zu ersetzen. Heute sind viele unterschiedliche Feldbussysteme mit unterschiedlichen Eigenschaften am Markt etabliert. Seit 1999 werden Feldbusse in der Norm IEC 61158 (Digital data communication for measurement and control - Fieldbus for use in industrial control systems) sowie durch die Norm IEC 61784 weltweit standardisiert. Die zweite Generation der Feldbustechnik basiert auf Echtzeit-Ethernet (Industrial Ethernet).

Class: MQTT. Definition: MQTT[1] (Message Queuing Telemetry Transport) is an ISO standard (ISO/IEC PRF 20922)[2] publish-subscribe-based messaging protocol. It works on top of the TCP/IP protocol. It is designed for connections with remote locations where a "small code footprint" is required or the network bandwidth is limited. The publish-subscribe messaging pattern requires a message broker.  Andy Stanford-Clark of IBM and Arlen Nipper of Cirrus Link authored the first version of the protocol in 1999.[3]  The specification does not specify the meaning of "small code footprint" or the meaning of "limited network bandwidth". Thus, the protocol's availability for use depends on the context. In 2013, IBM submitted MQTT v3.1 to the OASIS specification body with a charter that ensured only minor changes to the specification could be accepted.[4] MQTT-SN[5] is a variation of the main protocol aimed at embedded devices on non-TCP/IP networks, such as ZigBee.  Historically, the "MQ" in "MQTT" came from IBM's MQ Series message queuing product line.[6] However, queuing itself is not required to be supported as a standard feature in all situations.[7]  Alternative protocols include the Advanced Message Queuing Protocol (AMQP), Streaming Text Oriented Messaging Protocol (STOMP), the IETF Constrained Application Protocol,[8] XMPP,[9][10] DDS,[11] OPC UA,[12] and Web Application Messaging Protocol (WAMP). (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MQTT)

Class: SCTP. Definition: Es wurde von der Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) als neues Transportprotokoll vorgeschlagen und im Oktober 2000 in dem Standarddokument RFC 2960 veröffentlicht und im September 2007 durch RFC 4960 erweitert. Eine Einführung findet sich auch in RFC 3286. Das zuständige Gremium bei der IETF ist die Arbeitsgruppe Signaling Transport, kurz SIGTRAN.  Als Transportprotokoll steht SCTP auf derselben Stufe des TCP/IP-Referenzmodells wie TCP und UDP (Schicht 4 des OSI-Modells).  SCTP realisiert das Konzept einer Association: Hier wird eine Verbindung aufgebaut, in der mehrere Nachrichten-Datenströme in sich reihenfolgenerhaltend (untereinander aber potentiell nicht-reihenfolgenerhaltend) transportiert werden. Zusätzlich können einzelne, zum Beispiel dringende, Datagramme separat und außer der Reihe verschickt werden, die dadurch eventuell die In-Order-Datenströme „überholen“.  SCTP kennt außerdem Multistreaming und Multihoming (ein Host mit mehreren gültigen IP-Adressen). Es werden Heartbeats verwendet, um aktiv auf Verbindungsabriss zu testen.  Anders als TCP zeigt sich SCTP resistent gegen SYN-Flooding, eine Denial-of-Service-Attacke, bei der durch halboffene Verbindungen die Ressourcen des Servers aufgebraucht werden. Dazu verwendet es einen sogenannten Vier-Wege-Handshake. Hierbei speichert der Server bei einer Verbindungsanfrage (INIT-Paket) keine Zustandsinformationen, sondern schickt diese in Form eines Cookies (INIT-ACK-Paket) an den Client. Der Client muss dieses Cookie in seine Antwort (COOKIE-ECHO-Paket) einfügen und wird damit vom Server als zum Verbindungsaufbau berechtigt erkannt, was dieser ihm bestätigt (COOKIE-ACK-Paket). Ein ähnliches Verfahren ist mit TCP ebenfalls möglich, siehe SYN-Cookies.  Ursprünglich wurde SCTP als Transportprotokoll definiert, um Zeichengabenachrichten (SS7) aus Telefonnetzen auch über IP-Netzwerke übertragen zu können. Bei der Entwicklung stand insbesondere die Zuverlässigkeit des Protokolls im Vordergrund. SCTP ist aber auch für andere Anwendungen geeignet, da es Vorteile von TCP und UDP vereint. Eine wichtige, auf SCTP aufbauende Anwendung ist Reliable Server Pooling (RSerPool).  SCTP verwendet für Fluss- und Überlastkontrolle ähnliche Algorithmen wie TCP, verhält sich also in einem gemischten Netz (SCTP und TCP) neutral.[1]  Auch Java bietet seit Version 7 eine eigene API für SCTP an.

Class: SCTP. Definition: It was proposed by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) as a new transport protocol and published in October 2000 in the standard document RFC 2960 and extended in September 2007 by RFC 4960. An introduction can also be found in RFC 3286. The responsible body at the IETF is the Signaling Transport Working Group, or SIGTRAN for short.  As a transport protocol, SCTP is on the same level of the TCP/IP reference model as TCP and UDP (layer 4 of the OSI model).  SCTP implements the concept of an association: A connection is set up in which several message data streams are transported in a sequence-preserving manner (but potentially non-sequence-preserving among themselves). In addition, individual datagrams, for example urgent datagrams, can be sent separately and out of sequence, possibly "overtaking" the in-order data streams.  SCTP also knows multistreaming and multihoming (one host with several valid IP addresses). Heartbeats are used to actively test for connection failure.  Unlike TCP, SCTP is resistant to SYN flooding, a denial-of-service attack in which half-open connections use up the server's resources. It uses a so-called four-way handshake for this purpose. Here, the server does not store any state information in a connection request (INIT packet), but sends it to the client in the form of a cookie (INIT-ACK packet). The client must include this cookie in its response (COOKIE-ECHO packet) and is thus recognized by the server as authorized to establish a connection, which the server confirms to it (COOKIE-ACK packet). A similar procedure is also possible with TCP, see SYN cookies.  SCTP was originally defined as a transport protocol for transmitting signalling messages (SS7) from telephone networks over IP networks. During development, the reliability of the protocol was a particular focus. However, SCTP is also suitable for other applications because it combines the advantages of TCP and UDP. An important application based on SCTP is Reliable Server Pooling (RSerPool).  SCTP uses similar algorithms as TCP for flow and congestion control, so it behaves neutrally in a mixed network (SCTP and TCP)[1].  Java also provides its own API for SCTP since version 7.

Class: Number Of Gcars Sold Worldwide Per Year. Definition: The number of gasoline cars (gcars) sold worldwide in a year.

Class: Number Of Semiconductors Per Gcar. Definition: The number of semiconductors used in a gasoline car (gcar).

Class: Saving Rate Gcar. Definition: The energy savings rate or percentage achieved by a gasoline car (gcar).

Class: System (CO2). Definition: The carbon dioxide (CO2) emissions associated with the entire system or process.

Class: Total Energy Consumption Per Hour Gcar. Definition: The total energy consumption per hour for a gasoline car (gcar).

Class: Total Energy Saving Of Gcars Sold Worldwide In A Year. Definition: The total energy savings achieved by gasoline cars (gcars) sold worldwide in a year.

Class: Total Generated Energy From Last Year Wind Turbine. Definition: the cumulative amount of electrical energy generated by a wind turbine during the previous year. It represents the total power output produced by the wind turbine over a specific period, typically measured in kilowatt-hours (kWh) or megawatt-hours (MWh)
Class: Total Generated Energy From This Year Solar. Definition: The total generated energy from solar sources during the current year.

Class: Total Generated Energy From This Year Wind Turbine. Definition: the cumulative amount of electrical energy generated by a wind turbine during the current year. It represents the total power output produced by the wind turbine over a specific period, typically measured in kilowatt-hours (kWh) or megawatt-hours (MWh)
Class: Total Infrastructure. Definition: The infrastructure or facilities required for the operation or functioning of a unit.
Class: Total Saved Energy Per Hour Ecar. Definition: The total energy savings per hour for an electric car (ecar).
Class: Total Saved Energy Per Hour Gcar. Definition: The total energy savings per hour for a gasoline car (gcar).
Class: Total Saved Energy Per Hour Solar. Definition: The total energy savings per hour for solar panels.
Class: Total Saved Energy Per Hour Wind Turbine. Definition: The total energy savings per hour for wind turbines.
Class: Total Usage Time Of A Gcar. Definition: The total usage time of a gasoline car (gcar).
Class: Total Usage Time Of A Wind Turbine. Definition: The total usage time of a wind turbine.
Class: Total Usage Time Of An Ecar. Definition: The total usage time of an electric car (ecar).
Class: Total Usage Time Of Ecars Sold Worldwide In A Year. Definition: The total usage time of electric cars (ecars) sold worldwide in a year.
Class: Total Usage Time Of Gcars Sold Worldwide In A Year. Definition: The total usage time of gasoline cars (gcars) sold worldwide in a year.
Class: Total Usage Time Of Solar Panels Sold Worldwide Per Year. Definition: The total usage time of solar panels sold worldwide per year.
Class: Total Usage Time Of Wind Turbines Sold Worldwide In A Year. Definition: The total usage time of wind turbines sold worldwide in a year.
Class: Total Usage Time Solar. Definition: The total usage time of solar energy.
Class: Transportation. Definition: The various modes or means of transportation.
Class: Type Of The Transportation. Definition: The type or category of transportation, such as road, air, rail, or water.
Class: Wind Turbine. Definition: A device that converts wind energy into electricity.
Class: Activity. Definition: Additional lobes: Time
Class: Activity. Definition: An activity is something carried out over a specific time interval.

Class: Allocated Available To Promise. Definition: ALLOCATED AVAILABLE TO PROMISE is when scarce ATP quantities are allocated to different customer classes or customers. The resulting supply reservations are called allocated ATP (AATP) quantities.
Class: Allocation Plan. Definition: An allocation plan is a special plan, which deals with assigning ATP quantities to a customer or a customer class.
Class: Allocation Planning. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: Available To Promise. Definition: AVAILABLE TO PROMISE is the part of the inventory and projected supply that can be used to fulfill customer orders is called ATP.
Class: Batch Interval. Definition: This is the time span for which arriving orders are collected to derive for all of them jointly a first promised delivery date.

Class: Best Promised Delivery Date. Definition: This is the best delivery date the supplier ever promised to the customer. It represents the best delivery date the supplier submitted to the customer. Thus every later commitment or delivery is a de-commitment from the supplier.
Class: Complete Delivery. Definition: The normal case is that an order is completely delivered.

Class: Confirmed Delivery Date. Definition: The CDD is the committed date for order delivery that is communicated to the costumer. It depends on the communication strategy between manufacturer and customer. For instance, the CDD is the PDD if order repromising takes place in the same frequency as the update interval of the CDD.

Class: Customer. Definition: CUSTOMER is a person, organization, or business entity that generates demand by placing an order or making a request for a specific product or service. A customer may also fulfill their obligations by facilitating payment for the goods or services received.  Customers can be categorized into two main types:  •	External Customers: Entities outside the organization that purchase goods or services, often governed by agreements like Incoterms. •	Internal Customers: Stakeholders or departments within the organization that raise internal demand for products or services to support internal processes.  A customer interacts with the organization through actions such as order placement, demand generation, and the completion of financial transactions. Customers are central to both demand creation in the supply chain and the fulfillment processes that ensure the delivery of goods or services.

Class: Customer Class. Definition: CUSTOMER CLASS is the set of all customers is divided into different priority classes or segments based on certain criteria like profitability or importance of customer.
Class: Customer Order. Definition: This is an order that is initiated by a customer.
Class: Date. Definition: Additional lobe: Supply Chain

Class: Date. Definition: The availability date defines the point in time when the supply is available to the customer. It can be distinguished between different availability dates. Not all availability dates are communicated to the customer.
Class: Delivery Concept. Definition: The DELIVERY CONCEPT defines the terms and conditions for delivering an order to the customer. Partial and split delivery has to be taken into account.
Class: Delivery Date. Definition: This is the point in time when the customer received the requested order.

Class: Demand. Definition: DEMAND is a supply chain or production request for a specific product, product group or service. Either demand exists explicitly in form of customer need (e.g. orders or EDI forecast) or implicitly as expected customer need.
Class: Demand Class. Definition: The DEMAND CLASS is dividing the demand into priority classes.

Class: Demand Priority. Definition: DEMAND PRIORITY is the concept that is used to describe the different importance level of a demand. The demand priority can be assigned independently from the demand class.

Class: Engineering Lot. Definition: An engineering lot requires additional process development efforts and special attention during the production flow. Engineering lots have various functions, thus several engineering lot types can be differentiated.
Class: External Customer. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: Firm Order Demand. Definition: This is a special demand class that is used for demand that is required to fulfill already committed/accepted orders.
Class: First Promised Delivery Date. Definition: Initially, the FPD is set for an order delivery within the online order confirmation process.
Class: Forecasted Demand. Definition: This is a special demand class that is used for the projection of future demand.
Class: Internal Customer. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: Inventory Replenishment Demand. Definition: This is a special demand class that is used for replenishment of safety stock.
Class: Last Promised Delivery Date. Definition: This is the last commitment the supplier has given to the customer

Class: Location. Definition: LOCATION refers to a physical or virtual place where an action, process, or activity occurs, playing a critical role in the execution of tasks within the supply chain, production, and planning systems.  •	Logistics perspective: A location signifies the point where responsibility, ownership, or risk transitions between parties during the transfer of goods or services. •	Demand Fulfillment Perspective: A location represents the origin or destination of demand-related processes, such as the point of product dispatch, delivery to customers, or storage of inventory to meet customer needs. •	Planning Perspective: Locations are key inputs for planning activities, representing the physical sites or nodes in the supply chain (e.g., factories, warehouses, or distribution centers) where resources, capacity, or inventory must be allocated. •	Semiconductor Production Perspective: In manufacturing, a location indicates a specific site where production steps take place, such as fabrication, assembly, or testing.  LOCATIONS are fundamental to managing supply chain efficiency, tracking material flow, coordinating production processes, and ensuring timely fulfillment of customer orders.
Class: Lot. Definition: A lot is a set of wafers, substrates or modules that travel together through the FE or BE fab in order to fulfill a certain order.

Class: Master Plan. Definition: A master plan is a specific plan which determines which quantity resulting from confirmed orders and from forecasted demand should be completed in which location in which period of the planning horizon. Moreover, outsourcing decisions have to be represented in master plans.
Class: Master Planning. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: Online Order Promising Plan. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: Order. Definition: An ORDER contains at least one order position. An ORDER has an order type and is associated to DEMAND.

Class: Order Delivery Plan. Definition: This is the result of the order promise or repromise process for different sets of orders taking into account an allocation policy and the supply and allocation situation. Different order promising variants can be distinguished, for instance online order promising, batch order promising, and hybrid order promising. The same is true of repromising.
Class: Order Position. Definition: An ORDER POSITION refers to a product specification, a product quantity, and a desired delivery date. Each order position has a status and belongs to an order.

Class: Order Promising. Definition: This concept describes the process to promise an order considering allocation policy as well as supply and allocation situation. The order promising can be distinguished between different variants, for instance online order promising and batch order promising.
Class: Order Repromising Plan. Definition: No definition provided.

Class: Partial Delivery. Definition: It can be allowed that only parts of an order position of an order are delivered. Therefore, the customer is willing to waive parts of quantity belonging to an order position.
Class: Period. Definition: The concept period displays the sub unit of the planning horizon.
Class: Plan. Definition: A PLAN is an activity specification with an intended purpose.
Class: Planning. Definition: PLANNING is an activity with the purpose to determine a plan. Planning is associated with goals, represented by objective functions to be optimized.
Class: Planning Period. Definition: A planning period is a specific DateTimeInterval from the time ontology (Time Ontology 2020). It belongs to a planning window. It has a temporal duration.

Class: Planning Purpose. Definition: The PLANNING PURPOSE specifies the objectives of a certain planning activity. It is given by a set of performance measures that are related to a set of PLANNING OBJECTS.
Class: Planning Window. Definition: Planning in supply chains is associated with a planning window which is formed by a set of consecutive planning periods.

Class: Product. Definition: A PRODUCT is a good that fulfills a prescribed set of requirements (for instance, form, fit, and function). A set of alternative BOMs might be associated with each product. The manufacturing process is complicated by binning and substitution (in production). Binning refers to the process that an item can become one of several products based on tested levels of performance, for instance, speed.

Class: Product Aggregate. Definition: The concept product aggregate is used to group different products based on certain criteria. The grouping criteria depend on the planning purpose (e.g. controlling, production). It is a certain view (external or internal) on a set of products.

Class: Product Hierarchy. Definition: The concept characterizes the top-down and bottom-up relationship between different product aggregates. It organizes the product aggregates according to defined criteria.

Class: Production Strategy. Definition: The PRODUCTION STRATEGY determining which portions of a supply chain should operate in make to stock (MTS) mode, where production is driven by the replenishment of inventories at specific locations, and which in make to order (MTO) mode, where production is initiated to fulfill specific customer orders. The production strategy is related to the question where the customer order decoupling point (CODP), also referred to as the push-pull interface (or boundary) has to be placed. The CODP denotes the point in the supply chain where material is dedicated to a specific customer order to the degree that it cannot be used for another.
Class: Productive Lot. Definition: A productive lot is created to fulfill a customer demand. The production process is carried out as it is defined during the production development phase.

Class: Promised Delivery Date. Definition: This is the date for which eventually partial order delivery is confirmed. The PDD date can be changed over time. Within the repromising process there are typically different PDDs available.

Class: Replenishment Order. Definition: This is an order that is initiated by an internal request of the semiconductor manufacturer to produce the order according to a MTS strategy. The replenishment order can be divided into different sub order types, depending on the purpose of order creation.
Class: Requested Delivery Date. Definition: The RDD is the point in time when the customer wants to get the order.
Class: Route. Definition: Additional lobes: Semiconductor Production

Class: Route. Definition: The term route can be considered on different levels. In the present situation, a route is associated with a product and describes its production flow on the production network level.
Class: Split Delivery. Definition: It can be allowed that order positions of an order are delivered in several portions.

Class: Split Order. Definition: This is an order that results from a split delivery. When an order position of an order is delivered in several portions, each portion starting from the second one is considered as a separate suborder which is called scheduled order position. The original order also exists after the split.
Class: Supplier. Definition: A SUPPLIER is an entity fulfilling a demand for a specific product or service.

Class: Supply. Definition: SUPPLY is the total amount of specific products or services that is available to customers. Supply has the dimensions quantity, time, location, product, including aggregation of all dimensions. Supply is defined as inventory or plan replenishment.

Class: Supply Chain. Definition: A SUPPLY CHAIN is the network of organizations, resources, activities, and technologies involved in the production and delivery of a product from raw materials to the final customer. Supply chain management issues have become increasingly important to the semiconductor industry due to the global distribution of facilities and its inherent long production time.

Class: Supply Contract. Definition: A SUPPLY CONTRACT is a formal agreement between two parties—typically a supplier and a buyer—that outlines the terms and conditions under which goods or services will be provided over a specified period. The contract establishes a legally binding relationship and is commonly used in business-to-business transactions.
Class: Time Interval. Definition: Additional lobe: Planning

Class: Assemble To Order. Definition: In the case of ATO, products are produced forecast-driven until the point right before it comes to the assembly. Starting from there, the production continues based on a customer order.

Class: Bill Of Material (BOM). Definition: A BOM describes components or rather semi-finished products that are part of the finished product. Substitution, often associated with binning, is based on the possibility that alternative items might be used to finish a process step. This leads to the notion of alternative BOMs.
Class: Make To Order. Definition: This is a strategy where production is initiated to fulfill specific customer orders. This strategy is characterized by an order-driven production.

Class: Make To Stock. Definition: This is a strategy where production is driven by the replenishment of inventories at specific locations. Products are produced forecast-driven until they are completely finished in the case of MTS.

Class: Delivery Commitment. Definition: DELIVERY COMMITMENT refers to the agreed-upon date or timeframe by which a product, service, or solution is promised to be delivered to a customer. It is a key component of supply chain, project management, and customer service operations, ensuring alignment between supplier capabilities and customer expectations.

Class: Demand Snapshot. Definition: A DEMAND SNAPSHOT is a fixed capture of demand data at a given point in time. It allows comparison over time or alignment between supply and demand planning cycles.
Class: Demand Trace. Definition: DEMAND TRACE is the tracking of demand from final customer requests through the supply chain, enabling visibility of demand origins.
Class: Equipment. Definition: Equipment name. Machine of one equipment type that can execute certain production (or measurement) steps

Class: Lot_State. Definition: Covers all historical processes start and end of a lot in any facility and provides the full history of operations of a specific lot

Class: Incoterms_2020. Definition: The Incoterms or International Commercial Terms are a series of pre-defined commercial terms published by the International Chamber of Commerce (ICC) relating to international commercial law. They are widely used in international commercial transactions or procurement processes and their use is encouraged by trade councils, courts and international lawyers.  Incoterms 2020 is the ninth set of international contract terms published by the International Chamber of Commerce, with the first set having been published in 1936. Incoterms 2020 defines 11 rules, the same number as defined by Incoterms 2010.
Class: Incoterms_Application_Mode. Definition: Incoterms_Application_Mode is about the method of delivery the incoterm uses. An incoterm could use only ship or non-ship transport.
Class: Incoterms_Clause. Definition: An Incoterms_Clause is a term of the 11 pre-defined incoterms.
Class: Incoterms_Group. Definition: An Incoterms_Group is one of the four categories that describes incoterms rules.

LOCATIONS are fundamental to managing supply chain efficiency, tracking material flow, coordinating production processes, and ensuring timely fulfillment of customer orders.
Class: Offer. Definition: An OFFER is a proposal to provide goods, like products or services in exchange for something of value, such as money.
Class: Only_Ship_Transport_Clause. Definition: Incoterms that solely involve transportation by water.

Class: Product. Definition: PRODUCT is any tangible or intangible output that fulfills a prescribed set of requirements and is intended for delivery to a customer or end user. A product may result from mechanical, industrial, or other manufacturing processes and is created to meet specific customer needs, such as form, function, or performance.  Products can be classified as:  •	Tangible Products: Physical goods, such as semiconductor chips, electronic devices, or finished consumer electronics. •	Intangible Products: Services or deliverables that do not have a physical form but provide value, such as software, maintenance services, or intellectual property.  Products often involve complexities across their lifecycle, including manufacturing, transfer, and categorization. In manufacturing, they may use alternative Bills of Materials (BOMs) and processes like binning, categorizing variations based on performance (e.g., speed or functionality), with substitutions addressing supply chain constraints. Commercially, products serve as objects of transfer, shifting ownership or responsibility per agreements like Incoterms. They can also be represented as individual tangible instances (e.g., a smartphone), prototypes defining specifications, or placeholders for mass-produced commodities with unspecified details.
Class: Seller. Definition: SELLER is an entity which offers the services/goods.
Class: To_Location. Definition: A sub property of location. The final location of the object or the agent after the action.
Class: Transfer Action. Definition: TRANSFER ACTION is the act of transferring/moving objects from one place to another.
Class: Universal_Transport_Clause. Definition: Incoterms that may be used regardless of the method of transport.
Class: Action. Definition: ACTION is the process of doing something.
Class: n15569953ef7c46ba9a77e2a780e297d7b501. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: Allocation. Definition: ALLOCATION is a process used in supply chain (e.g. order management) in times when demand exceeds available supply.

Class: Contact Person Data. Definition: CONTACT PERSON DATA refers to the detailed information (name, role, email, phone) of a person responsible for handling specific transactions or communications in the supply chain process.

Class: Customer. Definition: CUSTOMER is a person, organization, or business entity that generates demand by placing an order or making a request for a specific product or service. A customer may also fulfill their obligations by facilitating payment for the goods or services received.  Customers can be categorized into two main types:  •	External Customers: Entities outside the organization that purchase goods or services, often governed by agreements like Incoterms. •	Internal Customers: Stakeholders or departments within the organization that raise internal demand for products or services to support internal processes.  A customer interacts with the organization through actions such as order placement, demand generation, and the completion of financial transactions. Customers are central to both demand creation in the supply chain and the fulfillment processes that ensure the delivery of goods or services.
Class: Customer Data. Definition: CUSTOMER DATA includes all information necessary to manage orders—such as identifiers, addresses, logistics preferences, and contractual conditions.

Class: Customer Plant. Definition: A CUSTOMER PLANT refers to the physical location or facility owned or operated by a customer where products, systems, or services are delivered, installed, maintained, or utilized.
Class: Customer Plant Data. Definition: CUSTOMER PLANT DATA refers to the structured and unstructured information associated with a customer's plant.
Class: Demand Fulfillement. Definition: DEMAND FULFILLEMENT is the process of meeting a customer´s demand for product or services by fulfilling their request.

Class: Demand Fulfillement. Definition: DEMAND FULFILLEMENT refers to the set of processes by which a company responds to customer demand by delivering products or services. In the semiconductor supply chain, it includes order promising, product allocation, scheduling, and ensuring timely delivery. It represents the interface between the supply chain and external customers, ensuring that demand is met in accordance with business rules and available resources. It represents the interface between the supply chain and its external customers.” It also connects closely with Available to Promise (ATP) mechanisms that decide what can be committed to customers based on current and projected inventory and capacity.

Class: Open Order. Definition: OPEN ORDER refers to a customer order that has been received and recorded in the system but has not yet been fully processed, shipped, or fulfilled. It represents a pending obligation within the sales or supply chain process.
Class: Open Order Book. Definition: OPEN ORDER BOOK refers to a real-time record of all active, unfulfilled customer orders within an organization. It includes detailed information on sales orders.

Class: Order Change Request. Definition: An ORDER CHANGE REQUEST is a formal request initiated by a customer or internal stakeholder to modify an existing order after it has been placed but before it is fully fulfilled or invoiced. This request can include changes to product quantities, item specifications, delivery dates, shipping addresses, or other order-related details.

Class: Order Confirmation. Definition: ORDER CONFIRMATION is a formal acknowledgment from the seller to the customer that an order has been received, reviewed, and accepted under the specified terms and conditions.

Class: Order Line Item. Definition: An ORDER LINE ITEM is an individual entry within a customer order that specifies the details of a specific product or service being purchased. Each line item represents a unique combination of product, quantity, and pricing, and collectively, line items make up the full contents of an order. A new order line item might be generated when partial fulfillment is committed or delivered.
Class: Supplier. Definition: A SUPPLIER is an entity fulfilling a demand for a specific product or service.
Class: Supplier Data. Definition: Information about a supplier.

Class: Supply. Definition: SUPPLY is the total amount of specific products or services that is available to customers. Supply has the dimensions quantity, time, location, product, including aggregation of all dimensions. Supply is defined as inventory or plan replenishment.

Class: User Action. Definition: USER ACTION refers to any interaction a user makes with a system, application, or interface—such as clicking a button, submitting a form, or navigating a page—that triggers a response or function.
Class: n15569953ef7c46ba9a77e2a780e297d7b505. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: Additional Power Management. Definition: A semiconductor product which is used within the context of additional power management

Class: Angle Sensor. Definition: Infineon offers a family of angle sensors based on integrated Magneto Resistive (ixMR) technologies. Technologies include today iGMR and AMR. The sensors detect the orientation of an applied magnetic field by measuring sine and cosine angle components with monolithically integrated magneto resistive elements. ixMR technology is now widely used in automotive and industrial applications and provides a wide range of benefits. Our iAMR sensors are ideal for applications with the highest accuracy requirements. Our iAMR technology offers best performance over temperature, lifetime and magnetic field range. They are pre-calibrated and ready to use.

Class: Digital Barometric Pressure Sensor. Definition: Infineon’s  DPS310 is a miniaturized digital barometric pressure sensor which offers high accuracy and low current consumption, and is capable of measuring both pressure and temperature. A sealed capacitive sensing element is used for pressure measurement, guaranteeing high precision and accuracy across temperature changes. The small package and low energy consumption make  DPS310 ideal for mobile applications and wearable devices.

Today the market demands smaller and more energy efficient Hall switches. To satisfy the needs of more compact designs and environmental legislation  with a high quality product is very difficult. Infineon offers attractive pricing, reliable supply, benchmark quality and excellent design-in support to contribute to the customers success.

The barometric air pressure (BAP) is an important parameter to compute the air-fuel ratio provided to the engine and for controlling spark advance to optimize engine efficiency. In automotive applications where high production volumes are common there is substantial interest in precision, low-cost and fully integrated sensors.

The stages of a motor control and drive solution are "Controller", "Driver", "Power Stage". These programmable linear Hall sensors come with different interface options. Our family of TLE499x linear Hall ICs is tailored to the needs of highly accurate angular and linear position detection and current measurement applications. Each product measures the vertical component of a magnetic field and outputs a signal that is directly proportional to the magnetic field. These programmable linear Hall sensors come with different interface options.

Class: Magnetic Current Sensor. Definition: A high-precision current sensor for industrial applications based on Infoneon proven Hall technology. The core-less concept significantly reduces footprint compared with existing solutions. Infineon´s TLI4970 is an easy-to-use, fully digital solution that does not require external calibration or additional parts such as A/D converters, 0 pAmps or reference voltage. It thus significantly reduces overall implementation effort as well as PCB space and cost.

Definition: The  magnetic speed sensors are designed to measure speed in safety and powertrain applications such as speedometers, ABS, camshafts/crankshafts and automatic transmissions. They are also used in similar applications in the industrial sector. The sensors use a ferromagnetic gear tooth or encoder structure to measure linear or rotational speed and position.

The BGT24M/L family is the largest and highest integrated 24GHz ISM band radar transceiver family currently in the market, providing a range of different transmitter and receiver channel configurations, supporting different application requirements. the sensor allows a Long range distance detection of moving objects up to 30 m and a wide range speed detection up to more than ±100 km/h.

Class: End Event. Definition: Denotes the event element that stands at the end of a branch in the process flow and thus, ends the process flow branch or the total process.

Class: Event. Definition: An event illustrates the fact that a process object has taken on a business relevant state influencing the further procedure of a process. Unlike a function, which is a time consuming occurrence, an event is related to one point in time. Therefore, it is used to describe an event or status in the process flow. The object is mandatory for: EPC start and EPC end or after x (xor), v (or).

Class: Event. Definition: The event is a passive element since it represents a change of state but does not cause it. Furthermore it can characterize the conditions and the results of an activity, which in turn triggers the next function. An event with no incoming arc is called start event, while an event with no outgoing arc is called end event.
Class: Function. Definition: The function type represents several action elements as task, process interfaces or business process activities.

Class: Function. Definition: They are the active elements of an EPC that represent the activities of a modelled process and again raise events upon completion. The extended event driven process chain expands the semantic of functions, since they may be associated with the organizational unit performing the function or the data needed and created as output by the function.
Class: Function Object. Definition: In IndustryPrint 5, function objects are used to model the decomposition of a process.
Class: Human Output. Definition: Human being that puts effort in the processing of a process step (function). It belongs to the organizational unit that is responsible for the specific process step.
Class: Input. Definition: Item external to a system (such as a process) that is transformed by the system (usually together with one or more other items) to become an output.
Class: Join Rule. Definition: Rule element that unites the control flow after being split into several branches. Has several incoming paths (at least two) and one outgoing.

Material can include but is not limited to raw and processed material, components, parts, assemblies, sub-assemblies, fuels, lubricants, coolants, cleaning agents, and small tools and accessories that may be consumed directly or indirectly.

Class: Model. Definition: One striking commonality between EPC meta models is the Process. One process may contain an unlimited number of elements, but a process element is always linked to a specific process. If a process contains an interface, it is always linked to one specific process and represents a refinement of a normal function.
Class: Model. Definition: To graphically depict functional and process decomposition, function objects are diagramed on models in IndustryPrint 5.
Class: Model Element. Definition: An EPC model element is part of the EPC meta model and can be represented by a Function, an Event, an Operator, a Process Interface.

Class: Model Element. Definition: Represents process flow elements except for modelling function objects.

Class: OR. Definition: At least one of the possible process paths must be followed.
Class: OR. Definition: It is responsible for splitting the control flow up in at least two different branches, due to an nonexclusive choice where one or several branches can be followed.

Class: OR. Definition: One or more incoming pathways required to proceed along the flow One or more outgoing pathways must be followed Used only when neither XOR nor AND can be used to better illustrate flow Has the weakest logic and should be used as sparingly as absolutely possible
Class: n15569953ef7c46ba9a77e2a780e297d7b620. Definition: No definition provided.

Class: Process. Definition: A collection of subprocesses that meet a specific business objective. E.g. Perform Sourcing or Purchase Materials and Services
Class: Process Diagram. Definition: The first level of process decomposition that is comprised of subprocesses that depict a business objective.

Class: Process Group Map. Definition: A set of a processes covering a single business area. Usually under the ownership of one business process owner and aligning with a function.

They thus facilitate process structuring and navigation by keeping models concise

Class: Process Interface. Definition: Process interfaces connect several process models on the same process hierarchical level by linking the EPCs according to their shared events (also known as "horizontal navigation"). They thus facilitate process structuring and navigation by keeping models concise and easy-to-read. Functionality: Jump function to next process (e.g. EPC, VAC), typically at the end of process branches. In the EPC flow there is an Event directly before.

Class: Process Type. Definition: A set of core and enabler processes of Infineon on Level 0 (highest level). This level helps helps organizing project work/ development and represents a single track in the oneSAP project. It is based on a Deloitte standard which was adapted to Infineon's needs.
Class: Process Type Map. Definition: A set of process types and related process groups that define the enterprise for a particular industry/sector.
Class: Role. Definition: Business Role (Person) that performs task.

Class: Rule. Definition: Rules allow to model alternative, exclusive alternative and parallel process flows.
Class: Screen. Definition: A transaction in SAP is described as a screen. Here, they represent the actions undertaken in the application SAP to perform a function in a process flow.
Class: Split Rule. Definition: Rule element that splits the control flow into several branches. Has one incoming path and several (at least two) outgoing paths.

Class: Industrial Sector. Definition: The collection of all localized groups of enterprises that are producers of industrial commodities, in which each such group together forms the major industrial sector for the region. 'Industrial commodities' includes MechanicalDevices and basic industrial materials. Examples include 'the world industrial sector', the 'industrial sector of China'. The Chinese water pump industry would not be an exemplar of IndustrialEconomicSector but would rather be a sub-industry (see subIndustries) of it. On the other hand, chinese water pump manufacturers would be considered groupMembers of 'the industrial sector of China'.  This classification is done by The Global Industry Classification Standard (GICS) is an industry taxonomy developed in 1999 by MSCI and Standard & Poor's (S&P) for use by the global financial community. The GICS structure consists of 11 sectors, 24 industry groups, 68 industries and 157 sub-industries[1] into which S&P has categorized all major public companies

Class: Information Object. Definition: A piece of information, such as a musical composition, a text, a word, a picture, independently from how it is concretely realized.

Class: Interface. Definition: A common boundary or interconnection between systems, equipment, concepts, or human beings
Class: Junction Temperature. Definition: The highest operating temperature of the actual semiconductor
Class: Leakage Current. Definition: No definition provided.

Class: Maximum Junction Temperature. Definition: Is specified in the part's datasheet and is used when calculating the necessary case-to-ambient thermal resistance for a given power dissipation.
Class: Microcontroller. Definition: Industrial sector of Microcontrollers

Class: Object. Definition: Any physical, social, or mental object, or a substance

Class: On-State Region. Definition: No definition provided.
