Class: n15569953ef7c46ba9a77e2a780e297d7b659. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: Operating Property. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: Operation Mode. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: P-Channel Configuration. Definition: No definition provided.

Class: Package. Definition: A package is the housing for a chip (or several chips) and provides electrical contacts. It is an interconnect in between chip-pads and the interface to the PCB board. A package is characterized by its outline (drawing) and its materials.
Class: Physical Object. Definition: Any physical object

Class: Platform. Definition: An Entity to which other Entities can be attached - particularly semiconductor products and other platforms.  Example: A post might act as the platform, a body might act as a platform for an attached device.
Class: Positive (+). Definition: Is the positive difference in electric potential between two points
Class: Power Converter. Definition: Industrial sector of Power Converters
Class: Price. Definition: The element of an entity
Class: Process. Definition: A process has an output and possibly inputs, and for a compositive process, describes the temporal and dataflow dependencies and relationships amongst its parts.
Class: Process Input. Definition: Any information that is provided a Procedure for its use.
Class: Process Output. Definition: Any information that is reported from a Procedure.

Class: Product. Definition: The superclass of all classes describing products or services types, either by nature or purpose. Examples for such subclasses are "TV set", "vacuum cleaner", etc. An instance of this class can be either an actual product or service (gr:Individual), a placeholder instance for unknown instances of a mass-produced commodity (gr:SomeItems), or a model / prototype specification (gr:ProductOrServiceModel). When in doubt, use gr:SomeItems. Examples: a) MyCellphone123, i.e. my personal, tangible cell phone (gr:Individual) b) Siemens1234, i.e. the Siemens cell phone make and model 1234 (gr:ProductOrServiceModel) c) dummyCellPhone123 as a placeholder for actual instances of a certain kind of cell phones (gr:SomeItems)
Class: Property. Definition: Any attribute of an entity

Class: Quality. Definition: Any aspect of an Entity (but not a part of it), which cannot exist without that Entity. For example, the way the surface of a specific PhysicalObject looks like is a Quality, while the encoding of that Quality into e.g. a PhysicalAttribute should be modeled as a Region. From the design viewpoint, the Quality-Region distinction is useful only when individual aspects of an Entity are considered in a domain of discourse. For example, in an automotive context, it would be irrelevant to consider the aspects of car windows for a specific car, unless the factory wants to check a specific window against design parameters (anomaly detection). On the other hand, in an antiques context, the individual aspects for a specific piece of furniture are a major focus of attention, and may constitute the actual added value, because the design parameters for old furniture are often not fixed, and may not be viewed as 'anomalies'.
Class: Real Estate. Definition: Real Estate sector
Class: Region Of Operation. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: Resistance. Definition: The degree to which a substance prevents the flow of an electric current through it
Class: Saturation Region. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: Semiconductor Product Data Sheet. Definition: Data sheet of a semiconductor product (its name), SiC MOSFET Data Sheet
Class: Semiconductors. Definition: Industrial sector of Semiconductors
Class: Semiconductors And Semiconductor Equipment. Definition: Industrial sector of Semiconductors and Semiconductor Equipment
Class: Sensors. Definition: Industrial sector of Sensors

Class: SiC MOSFET. Definition: Silicon Carbide Metal Oxide Semiconductor Field Effect Transistor (SiC MOSFET): It is a transistor: It is used for switching or amplifying the electronics signals or electric power.

Class: Situation. Definition: A view, consistent with ('satisfying') a Description, on a set of entities. It can also be seen as a 'relational context' created by an observer on the basis of a 'frame' (i.e. a Description). For example, a PlanExecution is a context including some actions executed by agents according to certain parameters and expected tasks to be achieved from a Plan; a DiagnosedSituation is a context of observed entities that is interpreted on the basis of a Diagnosis, etc. Situation is also able to represent reified n-ary relations, where isSettingFor is the top-level relation for all binary projections of the n-ary relation. If used in a transformation pattern for n-ary relations, the designer should take care of creating only one subclass of Situation for each n-ary relation, otherwise the 'identification constraint' (Calvanese et al., IJCAI 2001) could be violated.

Class: Social Object. Definition: Act of carrying out an (Observation) Procedure to estimate or calculate a value of a property of a FeatureOfInterest. Links to an ObservableProperty to describe what the result is an estimate of, and to a FeatureOfInterest to detail what that proeprty was associated with.  Example: The activity of estimating the intensity of an earthquake using the Mercalli intensity scale is an Observation as is measuring the moment magnitude, i.e., the energy released by said earthquake.
Class: Software And Services. Definition: Industrial sector of Software and Services
Class: Solar Energy. Definition: Area that focuses on solar energy solutions
Class: Source. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: Switcher. Definition: Switchers rapidly switch a series device on and off.
Class: Switching Frequency. Definition: No definition provided.

Class: Switching Value. Definition: The value of the result of the method (procedures) of the device function. The result is an information object that encodes some value for a feature. For example: a) If we consider the observation is the method used for sensing of the sensors, then the observation has a result which is the output of the sensor, b) If we consider the amplification is the method used for boosting of the power converter, then the amplification has a result which is the output of the  power converter,
Class: System. Definition: System is a unit of abstraction for pieces of infrastructure that implements procedure. A System may have components, its subsystems, which are other systems."
Class: Technology Hardware And Equipment. Definition: Industrial sector of Technology Hardware and Equipment
Class: The Application Voltage. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: The Device Output. Definition: SiC MOSFET Output, the device output is a piece of information (value), the value itself being represented by an The device function value.

Class: The Method Of The Device Function (Switching). Definition: The function of the devices has a method ( Procedure to estimate or calculate a value), for example: The Senor its function is the sensing, the sensing method is the observation The Boost converter ( a type of the power converter) its function is boosting, the boosting method is the amplification.  Act of carrying out an (the method) Procedure to estimate or calculate a value of a property of a FeatureOfInterest. Links to an the methodProperty to describe what the result is an estimate of, and to a FeatureOfInterest to detail what that proeprty was associated with.  Example: The activity of estimating the intensity of an earthquake using the Mercalli intensity scale is an Observation as is measuring the moment magnitude, i.e., the energy released by said earthquake."

Class: The Process Used In The Device Function. Definition: It is a process that results in the estimation, or calculation, of the value of a device output. Usually it derived from the name of the device for example: Sensor process: sensing: Sensing is a process that results in the estimation, or calculation, of the value of a phenomenon.  Boost Converter process: boosting: is a process that results in the estimation, or calculation, of the value of a amplified voltage.
Class: Threshold Voltage. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: Utilities. Definition: Utilities sector
Class: Variable Resistance. Definition: The variable degree to which a substance prevents the flow of an electric current through it
Class: Voltage. Definition: Is the difference in electric potential between two points
Class: Voltage Controlled. Definition: by applying the voltage between Gate and Sourcet o turn on, turn off the MOSFET, and  increaseing, decreasing  the MOSFET output current.
Class: Weight. Definition: The element of an entity
Class: Width. Definition: The width of an entity
Class: Triode/Constant Resistance Region. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: Activity. Definition: Additional lobes: Planning
Class: Automated. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: Autonomous. Definition: No definition provided.

Class: Available Capacity. Definition: : The AVAILABLE CAPACITY describes the ability of a resource within a period of time to perform activities or processes. Elmaghraby (2011) refers to this as operational capacity, i.e. the productive capacity that is obtained from the nominal capacity by subtracting the anticipated and unavoidable loss in productivity, for instance, due to machine breakdowns in a wafer fab.
Class: Bill Of Material. Definition: Additional lobe: Planning

Class: Bill Of Material. Definition: A BILL OF MATERIALS (BOM) describes the component products used to make another product. Substitution, often associated with binning, is based on the possibility that alternative items might be used to finish a process step.
Class: Bin. Definition: Additional lobe: Planning
Class: Binning. Definition: Additional lobe: Planning

Class: Binning. Definition: BINNING refers to the process of testing and categorizing parts against defined measures and sort them into different bins (Degbotse 2013). Each bin belongs to certain levels of defined measures (e.g. chip speed, current, voltage, energy consumption). Binning is often combined with SUBSTITUTION.

Class: Capacity. Definition: CAPACITY with respect to the Domain Semiconductor and Supply Chains Containing Semiconductor is the maximum number of products or a group of products a machine or a group of machines can produce. As soon as a machine has free capacity: 1. all lots which belongs to a priority class have to be dispatched immediately according to their priority rank.
Class: Component Part. Definition: No definition provided.

Class: Criteria. Definition: Typical CRITERIA are maximization, minimization, i.e. if an optimization problem is considered, or larger or smaller than a prescribed value of the certain performance measure, a so-called target, i.e. if a satisfaction problem is solved. In a multi-criteria setting, the dominance concept for plans is of interest.

Class: Decision Maker Type. Definition: We distinguish human decision-makers (human DECISION-MAKING UNITS) from fully automated DECISION-MAKING UNITS where computers make fully automated decisions. Between these two extremes there are semi-automated decisions, where a computer provides several decision alternatives and a human decision-maker chooses among them. Note that the decision-maker type can change over time.

Class: Decision Making Initiative. Definition: We distinguish fully autonomous DECISION-MAKING UNITS from DECISION-MAKING UNITS where the decision-making activities are triggered by other DECISION-MAKING UNITS. Note that the decision-making initiative can change over time in a situation-dependent manner.
Class: Decision Making Unit. Definition: The DECISION-MAKING UNIT specifies an instance that makes decisions.

Class: Decison Making Unit Character. Definition: In an ANTAGO¬NISTIC SETTING, the different DECISION-MAKING UNITS try to meet their own objectives which are in conflict. In a non-antagonistic setting, the DECISION-MAKING UNITS do not exploit their private knowledge in an opportunistic way.

Class: Demand. Definition: DEMAND is a supply chain or production request for a specific product, product group or service. Either demand exists explicitly in form of customer need (e.g. orders or EDI forecast) or implicitly as expected customer need.
Class: Dependent. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: Distributed Hierarchical Situation. Definition: In this situation, edges referring to instructions and reactions are possible.

Class: Edge. Definition: EDGE in the supply chain refers to the use of edge computing technologies to process data closer to where it is generated—such as warehouses, factories, vehicles or others —rather than relying on centralized cloud systems. By enabling real-time data analysis and decision-making at the "edge" of the network, companies can reduce latency, enhance operational responsiveness, and improve visibility across the supply chain.
Class: Frozen Fence. Definition: FROZEN FENCE is used to set a frozen interval in which decision making is not allowed, or a defined exception, to change the previously determined values.
Class: Heterarchical Situation. Definition: All the vertices have level 1.

Class: Hierarchical Situation. Definition: HIERARCHICAL SITUATION refers to the structured, multi-level arrangement of entities, processes, or decision-making authority within the supply chain. It outlines e.g. how different layers—such as suppliers, manufacturers, distributors, and retailers—interact based on levels of control, responsibility, and information flow.
Class: Human. Definition: No definition provided.

Class: In-Transit Inventory. Definition: The IN-TRANSIT INVENTORY describes the quantity of a certain product that is shipped from one location to another. This quantity has left the inventory of one location, but has not yet been received into the inventory of the receiving location.

Class: Inventory. Definition: INVENTORY refers to the stock of goods, materials, and components that a business holds for the purpose of production, resale, or operational use. It is a key asset in supply chain and financial management, directly impacting a company's ability to meet customer demand, manage costs, and generate revenue.

Class: Inventory Policy. Definition: INVENTORY POLICY is a set of rules that guide how much stock is needed to balance supply with demand. It helps prevent shortages or excess inventory while controlling costs.

Class: Location. Definition: LOCATION refers to a physical or virtual place where an action, process, or activity occurs, playing a critical role in the execution of tasks within the supply chain, production, and planning systems.  •	Logistics perspective: A location signifies the point where responsibility, ownership, or risk transitions between parties during the transfer of goods or services. •	Demand Fulfillment Perspective: A location represents the origin or destination of demand-related processes, such as the point of product dispatch, delivery to customers, or storage of inventory to meet customer needs. •	Planning Perspective: Locations are key inputs for planning activities, representing the physical sites or nodes in the supply chain (e.g., factories, warehouses, or distribution centers) where resources, capacity, or inventory must be allocated. •	Semiconductor Production Perspective: In manufacturing, a location indicates a specific site where production steps take place, such as fabrication, assembly, or testing.  LOCATIONS are fundamental to managing supply chain efficiency, tracking material flow, coordinating production processes, and ensuring timely fulfillment of customer orders.
Class: Lot Sizing Rule. Definition: Additional lobe: Planning

Class: Lot Sizing Rule. Definition: A LOT SIZING RULE defines a rule to specify the lot size for a specific part. The lot size on the other hand defines the number of pieces belonging to a part. The lot size is the result of applying lot sizing rules.
Class: Macro Operation. Definition: Additional lobe: Planning
Class: Order. Definition: An ORDER contains at least one order position. An ORDER has an order type and is associated to DEMAND.
Class: Owner. Definition: An OWNER refers to the individual, team, or entity that holds primary responsibility for a specific asset, process, task, or decision within an organization or project.
Class: Part. Definition: Additional lobe: Planning

Class: Part. Definition: A PART represents a physical instance of a product in the manufacturing process. It therefore realizes a product. A part moves through the system and is manufactured according to its product specification. A part is associated to exactly one product. During the production process it is typically tested several times. The binning rules of the associated product specification can be applied to the respective part. A part can be substituted by another part according to the associated product specification

Class: Performance Measure. Definition: PERFORMANCE MEASURE is defined by a calculation procedure. Performance measures can be blended using weights to express the importance of the different measures.
Class: Plan. Definition: A PLAN is an activity specification with an intended purpose.

Class: Plan Execution. Definition: A PLAN EXECUTION is related to performing the activities according to a PLAN either directly in the base system, for instance, releasing lots into a wafer fab, or as instructions for another DECISION-MAKING UNIT.
Class: Planning Approach. Definition: PLANNING APPROACH is a specific planning algorithm which is used in a deticated planning process.

Class: Planning Constraint. Definition: In the planning domain a PLANNING CONSTRAINTS is often referred to capacity limitation, which limit the quantities that can be produced on an equipment or a fab for a certain product or product groups. Other Constraints can be workforce or material. Constraints can be temporary and can change.  Most popular academic definition: A PLANNING CONSTRAINT restricts the action space. This space is formed by alternative actions that are a result of the planning decisions (Schneeweis 2003).
Class: Planning Decision. Definition: The PLANNING DECISIONS is the best choice out of options, determined by the DECISION-MAKING UNIT.
Class: Planning Function. Definition: PLANNING FUNCTION describes the different functions and its properies follwing the supply chain planning matrix.
Class: Planning Instance. Definition: A PLANNING INSTANCE specifies the PLANNING OBJECTS and the values of related PLANNING CONSTRAINTS that form the basis for a planning decision.

Class: Planning Object. Definition: A PLANNING OBJECT specifies what has to be planned as an atomic unit. A single PLANNING OBJECT typically represents a quantity of a certain product or product aggregate to be released or completed within a certain period in a certain node of the semiconductor supply chain. Other PLANNING OBJECTS can be orders or lots. Values are assigned to the attributes of a PLANNING OBJECT as a result of a planning decision.
Class: Planning Process. Definition: The PLANNING PROCESS specifies under which circumstances which (re)planning activities are performed by a DECISION-MAKING UNIT.

Class: Planning Purpose. Definition: The PLANNING PURPOSE specifies the objectives of a certain planning activity. It is given by a set of performance measures that are related to a set of PLANNING OBJECTS.
Class: Planning Situation. Definition: The PLANNING SITUATION describes the organization of several DECISION-MAKING UNITS and also its environment.

Class: Process. Definition: A PROCESS is a collection of subprocesses that meet a specific business objective. E.g. Perform Sourcing or Purchase Materials and Services. A production PROCESS specifies a method of making a product at a location. The process is expressed at a coarse level of granularity suitable for use in production planning.

Class: Product. Definition: A PRODUCT is a good that fulfills a prescribed set of requirements (for instance, form, fit, and function). A set of alternative BOMs might be associated with each product. The manufacturing process is complicated by binning and substitution (in production). Binning refers to the process that an item can become one of several products based on tested levels of performance, for instance, speed.

Class: Product Aggregate. Definition: A PRODUCT AGGREGATE combines individual products into a product group, called a PRODUCT AGGREGATE. This results in a reduction of complexity, which enables a better overview.

Class: Product Hierarchy. Definition: A PRODUCT HIERARCHY characterizes the top-down and bottom-up relationship between different product aggregates. It organizes the product aggregates according to defined criteria. A product aggregate is used to group different products based on certain criteria. The grouping criteria depends often on the planning purpose (e.g. controlling, production). It is a certain view on a set of products.
Class: Projected WIP. Definition: Additional lobe: Planning
Class: Projected WIP. Definition: The PROJECTED WIP describes the quantity of a certain product that is anticipated to be received into inventory at a particular location at a particular time.
Class: Replanning Degree. Definition: REPLANNING DEGREE is the degree of change between an updated plan and a previous plan.
Class: Required Capacity. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: Resource. Definition: Additional lobe: Planning
Class: Resource Availability Constraints. Definition: This type of constraints has an impact on the assignment of activities to RESOURCES and to START/END TIMES to ACTIVITIES.
Class: Resource Compatibility Constraints. Definition: This type of constraints ensures that only allowed activities are performed using a given RESOURCE.
Class: Route. Definition: Additional lobe: Planning

Class: Semi Automated. Definition: Between these two extremes there are semi-automated decisions, where a computer provides several decision alternatives and a human decision-maker chooses among them.
Class: Strict_Hierarchical_Situation. Definition: There are only edges between vertices of level k and vertices of level k-1, where k≥2.
Class: Substitution. Definition: Additional lobe: Planning

Class: Substitution. Definition: SUBSTITUTION refers to using alternative parts. Depending on the product, each one could be replaced by using specific alternatives at the same stage of production, e.g. final product, raw material, or semi-finished products (Degbotse 2013) in order to complete a manufacturing step or fulfill a customer order.
Class: Supply Information. Definition: SUPPLY INFORMATION provides information of the used and unused supply of a supply chain network.
Class: Target. Definition: TARGETS are prescribed values for the different performance measures.

Class: Temporal-Constraints. Definition: This type of constraints restricts the values of temporal attributes, modeled by the property TIME, that belong to PLANNING OBJECTS. For instance, there might be a minimum amount of time between two consecutive operations of a certain product.
Class: Trigger. Definition: Additional lobe: Planning

Class: Trigger. Definition: A mechanism that initiates an action when an event occurs such as reaching a certain time or date or upon receiving some type of input. A trigger generally causes a program routine to be executed.

Class: Vertex. Definition: VERTEX plays a crucial role in the financial and compliance side of the supply chain. Its solutions help businesses calculate, manage, and report indirect taxes (like sales tax, VAT, and GST) at the relevant point in the supply chain, from procurement to distribution.
Class: Yield. Definition: Additional lobe: Planning
Class: Yield. Definition: YIELD could be the fraction (percentage) of good dies resulting from total dies released.
Class: Admin Shell. Definition: Andmin Shell represents and describes an asset elecrtonically in a standardized manner

Class: Asset. Definition: Every I4.0-component has to represent an entity. The entity can be physical or digital asset. The definition makes it possible to classify assets without integrated and accessible computers as I4.0-component, if the digital representation of the asset is accessible on a separate computer.
Class: Date. Definition: A numbered day in a month, often given with a combination of the name of the day, the month, and the year
Class: Dimension. Definition: Abstract class to describe the three different dimensions of RAMI4.0
Class: Energy Efficiency. Definition: Specifies some details regarding energy efficiency. These can also be supplied by sensors.
Class: I 4.0 Component. Definition: Globally uniquely identifiable participant with communication capability consisting of administration shell and asset within an I4.0 system.

Class: MES Connection. Definition: Connects the station to a higher-level MES system via a small number of properties. Specifies whether the station is producing, ready for production, has a fault or is undergoing maintenance, for example.
Class: Machine. Definition: A machine is ordered, designed, commissioned, operated, serviced, converted and recycled.
Class: Measure. Definition: To discover the exact size or amount of something

Class: RAMI Hierarchy Level Dimension. Definition: It describes the functional classification of various circumstances within Industrie 4.0. For classification within a factory, this axis of the reference architecture(layers) follows the IEC 62264 Standard.
Class: n15569953ef7c46ba9a77e2a780e297d7b665. Definition: No definition provided.

Class: RAMI IT Layer Dimension. Definition: The six layers on the vertical axis describe the decomposition of a machine into its properties, structured layer by layer, i.e., the virtual mapping of a machine. Such representations originate from information and communication technology, where properties of complex systems are commonly broken down into layers.
Class: n15569953ef7c46ba9a77e2a780e297d7b673. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: RAMI Life Cycle Dimension. Definition: It describes the different Life Cycle and Value Stream layers for the RAMI model according to the IEC 62890 Standard.
Class: n15569953ef7c46ba9a77e2a780e297d7b680. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: Semantic Expression. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: n15569953ef7c46ba9a77e2a780e297d7b683. Definition: No definition provided.

Class: Sensor. Definition: Device, agent (including humans), or software (simulation) involved in, or implementing, a Procedure. Sensors respond to a stimulus, e.g., a change in the environment, or input data composed from the results of prior Observations, and generate a Result. Sensors can be hosted by Platforms.
Class: Sensor Measurement. Definition: Measurement performed by a sensor
Class: Standard. Definition: Standards that are used to describe the actual I4.0 Asset. Defined in the STO ontology
Class: Standard Organization. Definition: Standards organisations that prepares and publishes International Standards for all electrical, electronic and related technologies
Class: Standard Version. Definition: Most commonly used version
Class: Structure. Definition: The way in which the parts of a system or object are arranged or organized, or a system arranged in this way
Class: Submodel. Definition: Describe the different types of data related to the I4.0 asset
Class: Transport Interface. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: Used Date. Definition: Date uded by particular standard
Class: Version. Definition: A particular form of something that is slightly different from other forms of the same thing
Class: View. Definition: Different views associated to the Administration Shell via the Submodels
Class: n15569953ef7c46ba9a77e2a780e297d7b687. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: AP FCST. Definition: No definition provided.

Class: Aggregated Capacity. Definition: The AGGREGATED CAPACITY GROUP (ACG) combines products that are interchangeable in production resources (e.g. can be produced on the same equipment) and having the same capacity consumption. Using an ACG provides flexibility in a way of switching demands of this products within this ACG.

Class: Allocated Available To Promise. Definition: The AATP (Allocated Available To Promise) is this part of the ATP (Available To Promise) which is already located to a certain customer(group) or a region.
Class: Available To Promise. Definition: The ATP (Available to promise) is todays and upcoming Availability of products for demand fulfillment and order promising.
Class: Bottleneck Resource. Definition: A bottleneck resource is an obstacle to smooth flow in a process.
Class: Buffer Stock Order. Definition: No definition provided.

Class: Capacity Bottleneck. Definition: A CAPACITY BOTTLENECK describes a machine or another element, which constrains the flow of a product. The throughput of the Capacity Bottlenecks define the throughput of a production line.
Class: Confirmation. Definition: A CONFIRMATION is an order acknowledgement with a due date from the supplier.

Class: Consignment Order. Definition: Consignment Stock is a logistics concept where the supplier (Vendor) owned goods are stored at a customer location.  The supplier (Vendor) is responsible to maintain his stock within a defined min/max level.

Class: Customer. Definition: CUSTOMER is a person, organization, or business entity that generates demand by placing an order or making a request for a specific product or service. A customer may also fulfill their obligations by facilitating payment for the goods or services received.  Customers can be categorized into two main types:  •	External Customers: Entities outside the organization that purchase goods or services, often governed by agreements like Incoterms. •	Internal Customers: Stakeholders or departments within the organization that raise internal demand for products or services to support internal processes.  A customer interacts with the organization through actions such as order placement, demand generation, and the completion of financial transactions. Customers are central to both demand creation in the supply chain and the fulfillment processes that ensure the delivery of goods or services.

Class: Customer Logistics Management Representative. Definition: A CUSTOMER LOGISTICS MANAGEMENT REPRESENTATIVE (CLM) is a typical name for one “face” to the customer, taking care of all customers supply chain topics. He/she is responsible for the demand fulfilment process – Usage of ATP. It is his/her task to ensure in-time delivery to customers based on orders and forecasts. He/she is usually also taking care of forecast in a midterm time horizon (typical for that is the EDI FORECAST)
Class: DC. Definition: A DC Facility represents a finished goods store.
Class: Die Bank. Definition: A die bank is an area in production where (usually) tested wafers are stored waiting for disposition and further production.
Class: EDI Forecast. Definition: The EDI Forecast Universe is a Data Mart that was started in 2010 (?) to support Forecast Accuracy  analysis
Class: Forecast. Definition: Forecast is an unconstrained prospect about the customer future demand.
Class: General Customers. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: HP Forecast. Definition: No definition provided.

Class: Marketing Demand. Definition: MARKETING DEMAND is a supply chain or production request for a specific product, product group or service, coming from the market. Either demand exists explicitly in form of customer need (e.g. orders or EDI forecast) or implicitly as expected customer need.

Class: Max Stock. Definition: The amount of inventory which should not be exceeded. The limit is normally determined after considering storage space of the facilities, how quickly inventory is sold or used, cost of insurance on inventory, and the risk of inventory becoming outdated before it is used.

Class: Min Stock. Definition: The minimum level of inventory is a kind of a precautionary level of inventory which indicates that the delivery of raw materials or merchandise may take more than the normal lead time.

Class: Min Stock. Definition: The minimum level of stock is a certain predetermined minimum quantity of raw materials or product inventory which should always be available in stock in the normal course of business.

Class: nEWs. Definition: A nEW is a negative Early Warning and it means that a new customer order confirmation is worse (later order confirmation date) than the previous order confirmation. nEWs is the plural of nEW.
Class: NP Forecast. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: OP Forecast. Definition: No definition provided.

Class: Open Order Book. Definition: An OPEN ORDER BOOK is a business's list of open, unshipped, customer orders, normally time-phased and valued at actual individual order prices, that may include margin and profitability analysis.

Class: Operational Demand. Definition: OPERATIONAL DEMAND is a supply chain or production request for a specific product, product group or service, coming from company intern business division. Either demand exists explicitly in form of customer need (e.g. orders or EDI forecast) or implicitly as expected customer need.OPERATIONAL DEMAND is a supply chain or production request for a specific product, product group or service, coming from company intern business division. Either demand exists explicitly in form of customer need (e.g. orders or EDI forecast) or implicitly as expected customer need.
Class: Order. Definition: An ORDER is a confirmation of a transaction (a receipt), which can contain multiple line items, each represented by an Offer that has been accepted by the customer.

Class: Order Line Item. Definition: ORDER LINE ITEM is every product on the order is referenced by a record that includes quantity and usually a customer delivery wish date, as well as a reference to which order it belongs.
Class: Order Reschedule. Definition: ORDER RESCHEDULE is any change in the requested order delivery date or volume in an order line is referred to as an order rescheduling.
Class: Order Schedule Line. Definition: ORDER SCHEDULE LINE contains all the delivery related information.
Class: Prioritized Demand. Definition: The PRIORITIZED DEMAND is the demand that should be covered first.
Class: Prioritized Orders. Definition: PRIORITIZED ORDERS are Orders that should be completed first.
Class: Private Customers. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: Promise. Definition: A PROMISE is the committed portion of supply by the master production schedule and material plan.
Class: Ramp Up Stock. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: Resource Capacity. Definition: Resource capacity planning is about comparing future resource utilization of project resources against available capacity to do work.
Class: Retained Stock. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: SSO Stocks. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: Safety Stock. Definition: Describes a level of extra stock that is maintained to mitigate risk of stockouts  caused by uncertainties in supply and demand.

Class: Sales Demand. Definition: A SALES DEMAND is a request for a specific product or service that can have different triggers. Either demand exists explicitly in form of customer orders or implicitly as expected customer need that have to be fulfilled by the semiconductor supply chain.
Class: Standard Order. Definition: No definition provided.
Class: Stocks. Definition: A supply of something for use or sale
Class: Supply Demand Match. Definition: Supply and demand match when sufficient materials exist to cover material demand while taking available capacity into account.

Class: Supply Picture. Definition: A SUPPLY PICTURE is a visualization of the supply in its dimensions. Supply is the total amount of specific products that is available to customers. Supply has the dimensions quantity, time, location, product, including aggregation of all dimensions. Supply is defined as inventory or plan replenishment.
Class: Target Allocation. Definition: The TARGET ALLOCATION is the level of allocation planned by the company.

Class: Work In Progress. Definition: Work In Progress (WIP) includes the unfinished items for products in a production process. These items are not yet completed but either just being fabricated or waiting in a queue for further processing.
Class: Bottleneck. Definition: A capacity Bottleneck is defined as an equipment or multiple equipment that reflect the capacity of the whole line (either a dedicated Line or Pool sharing).

Class: Capacity. Definition: CAPACITY with respect to the Domain Semiconductor and Supply Chains Containing Semiconductor is the maximum number of products or a group of products a machine or a group of machines can produce. As soon as a machine has free capacity: 1. all lots which belongs to a priority class have to be dispatched immediately according to their priority rank.

Class: Chemical Polishing. Definition: The chemical polishing process or chemical mechanical planarization (CMP) is a process whereby a chemical reaction increases the mechanical removal rate of a material. CMP is commonly used to polish off high spots on wafers or films deposited on wafers, flattening the film or wafer, referred to as planarization. The chemical reaction that increases the mechanical removal rate is commonly tailored to provide a higher removal rate of one material versus another material. The chemical action in CMP helps to achieve higher selectivity's of one material to another than a strictly mechanical process would provide.
Class: Current Work In Progress. Definition: “Current WIP” entity describes the actual material distribution in the supply chain. (snapshot entity)
Class: Cycle Time Commitment. Definition: The “Cycle Time Commitment” entity helps controlling the WIP via the release plan. (strategy entity)
Class: Delivery Commitment. Definition: The "Delivery Commitment" directly corresponds to the release plans and cycle time commitments introduced in the corresponding entities.
Class: Demand Snapshot. Definition: The “Demand” entity stores redundant demand at every product level. (snapshot entity)

Class: Deposition. Definition: The deposition process, or chemical vapor deposition (CVD) is a process whereby a fiolm is deposited by reacting chemicals together in the gaseous or vapor phase to form a film. The gases or vapors utilized for CVD are compounds that contain the element to be deposited and that may be inducted to react with a substrate or other gas(es) to deposit a film. The CVD reactoin may be thermally activated, plasma induced, plasma enhanced CVD or activated by light in photon induced CVD.
Class: Development. Definition: These lots have the same maxium waiting time as standard lots, however they are put before the standard lots.

Class: Diffusion. Definition: Diffusion is a process whereby a substance redistributes from an area of relatively high concentration to an area of relatively low concentration due to random thermal motion. The larger the concentration gradient the faster diffusion occurs for a given temperature, conversely, the higher the temperature the faster diffusion occurs for a given concentration gradient.

Class: Dry Etching. Definition: Dry etching is a process whereby etching is accomplished by a reactive gas as opposed to a liquid. Dry etching techniques include plasma etch, reactive ion etch, magnetically enhanced reactive ion etch, inductively coupled plasma, electron spin resonance, etc.
Class: EPA. Definition: The EPA is a product identifier referring to the associated process.

Class: Equipment. Definition: The entity “Equipment” describes the semiconductor equipment of any equipment model. It allocates it to higher level entities and describes the behavior of the equipment. (master entity)

Class: Equipment Group. Definition: Each machine is allocated to a group of machines doing similar processes. The equipment groups are described and allocated in the master entity “Equipment Group”. (master entity)
Class: Event Calendar. Definition: In the “Event Calendar” tracing entity, certain events like planned facility shutdowns, etc. can be scheduled
Class: Fabrication. Definition: The “Fab” entity depicts the fab as a technological and physical production unit. (master entity)
Class: Furnace. Definition: Each furnace consists of two chambers with one tool in each chamber.

Class: Furnace Process. Definition: Sequence of interdependent and linked procedures which, at every stage, consume one or more resources (employee time, energy, machines, money) to convert inputs (data, material, parts, etc.) into outputs. These outputs then serve as inputs for the next stage until a known goal or end result is reached.

Class: Hot. Definition: These lots are processed after a certain maximum waiting time which is shorter than the maximum waiting time of standard lots. In general, for all classes, if there is more than one product type waiting.

Class: Implantation. Definition: Implantation or Ion Implantation is a technique where ions are accelerated to a higher energy and speed an injected into a semiconductor. The dominant techniques for introducing dopants into a semiconductor.

Class: Lithography. Definition: The lithography process is the key process in frontend. This consists of the following steps: a photo resisting layer is spun on a wafer, then exposed through the mask, then developed, then showing the effect on the open places, and then final deletion of the photo resisting material leaves only the remaining structure on the water. after some time for deposition, these steps are repeated up to 35 times.
Class: Lot. Definition: The Lot represents manufacturing unit (e.g. in the semicondutor industry in Frontend this often consists of 25 or 50 wafers).
Class: Lot Event. Definition: The Lot Event  tracing entity gives the history of lot events. e.g. Hold events, Split events, Merge events, etc. (tracing entities).
Class: Lot Size. Definition: A measure or quantity increment acceptable to or specified by the party offering to buy or sell. Used also as an alternative term for lot quantity.

Class: Mask. Definition: A transparent (glass or quartz) plate covered with an array of patterns used in making an IC. Each pattern consists of opaque and transparent areas that define the size and shape of all circuit and device elements. The mask is used to expose selected areas, and defines the areas to be processed. Masks may use emulsion, chrome, iron oxide, silicon or other material to produce the opaque areas.
Class: Material Transfer Matrix. Definition: A material transfer matrix estimates the duration of material from on to another equipment.

Class: Operation. Definition: The master entity “Operation” depicts the generic behavior of a single process step. Each operation has a foreign key relation to equipment and to route which means that the operation is required by the specific routes and requires a specific equipment. (workflow descriptive master entity)
Class: Operator. Definition: A user that interacts with the equipment only to the degree necessary for the equipment to perform its intended function.
Class: Owner. Definition: An owner is the entity that has the highest level of access authority or legal right to a system or equipment.

Class: Planning Work Center. Definition: Semiconductor wafers arrive at the planning work center according to a Poisson process in lots with a certain unit size. The planning work center X48- can process three different products which arrive in four different classes.

Class: Plant. Definition: The “Plant” entity describes the plant as a physical location of one or more fabs. The Plant belongs to a supply chain and can either be internal or external. (master entity)
Class: Priority Class. Definition: Each lot is characterized by a product type and a priority class. The priority classes are listed as follows: development, hot, productive, rocket and timecoupling.

Class: Process. Definition: Sequence of interdependent and linked procedures which, at every stage, consume one or more resources (employee time, energy, machines, money) to convert inputs (data, material, parts, etc.) into outputs. These outputs then serve as inputs for the next stage until a known goal or end result is reached.
Class: Process. Definition: Additional lobe: Semicondutor Development

Class: Process Class. Definition: A Process Class is the second hierarchy level in the Technology Catalogue and is a subset of top hierarchy level "Technology Class". A Process Class is defined by the device category and its generation or wafer diameter.

Class: Process Flow. Definition: A wafer technology is defined as a manufacturing process flow on wafer level including wafer test and pre-assembly which creates one device (discrete technology) or a set of different devices (IC technology) to be used in a product.

Class: Process Group. Definition: A Process Group is the third hierarchy level in the Technology Catalogue and a subset of the Process Class. A Process Group is defined by the device type and its generation (eventually voltage class) or wafer diameter
Class: Process Line. Definition: A Process Line is the forth hierarchy level in the Technology Catalogue and is a subset of Process Group. A Process Line is defined by WHAT is produced in detail
Class: Product. Definition: A product is a work product that is delivered to the customer.
Class: Product. Definition: A product is any tangible output or service that is a result of a process and that is intended for delivery to a customer or end user.

Class: Product Class. Definition: the product class is an entity used for planning and reporting. This helps create stable brand/name architectures to enable highest possible product portfolio transparency, true value creation ad to prevent from product TM overload.
Class: Product Group. Definition: A (main) product group is a grouping of products for calculation or sales purposes. The scope includes finished and unfinished products of one product line.

Class: Product Level. Definition: In the "product level" entity, the aggregation of elements enables the grouping of products and defines the relationship between products and groups at different hierarchy levels. This supports planning, logistics, modeling, forecasting and reporting.
Class: Product Level 2. Definition: The product levels 3 to 1 are aggregated levels that are based on information from product level 4. (hierarchal aggregation level)

Class: Product Level 3. Definition: The static bottlenecks are determined in the “Product Level 3” master entity because the mid capacity planning is done on this first aggregated product level. There is no big difference in capacity from the aggregated level 3 product to its child level 4 products. (hierarchal aggregation level)
Class: Product Line. Definition: The product line is one of the most prominent grouping of products. It is used in reporting as well as for structuring organizations.
Class: Product Number. Definition: The product number is a unique identifier of a product. The scope is limited to finished products only.
Class: Production Request. Definition: Production requests definte what the facilities need to produce when and in what quantity.
Class: Productive. Definition: The standard lots, also referred to as Productive (Prod) lots, are the most common lot type and have no priority.

Class: Purge. Definition: purge' is the application of an intert gas, or gas mixture, to the OD or ID surface of the weld joint to displace non-inert atmospheric gases. A block purge is a non-flowing purge with positive pressure.
Class: Release Plan. Definition: The “Release Plan” entity shows the quantity planned to be released to a fab or facility. (strategy entity)
Class: Robot. Definition: The robot loads and unloads the lots from the WIP station into the furnace. Robot can load the furnace while another boat is processd by the tool.
Class: Rocket. Definition: Rocket lots are processed immediately if a machine has free capacity. The remaining furnace space is then filled up with lots of the same product.

Class: Route. Definition: The master entity “Route” describes the structure of a workflow out of operations. Every product uses a specific route in its value stream, i.e. the complete sequence of operations with all mandatory and optional operations necessary to complete the product. A route makes use of the single operations. (workflow descriptive master entity)
Class: Shift. Definition: Each workshop has a certain technical and operational workforce organized in shifts described in the “Shift” entity.

Class: Simulation Part. Definition: A simulation part helps to identify the same product in different locations. They are visible in Product Structures. This is a simulation entity and not a form of production/planning.

Class: Simulation Route. Definition: A simulation route (AKA workroute) represents a sequence of process steps in manufacutring (mainly at wafer fab). This is a simulation entity and not a form of production/planning.

Class: Sputtering. Definition: The sputtering process, or physical vapor deposition (PVD) is the most used layering process today. Here gas atoms, mostly argon, strike out atoms from the cathode I an electric field which then form a thin film on the wafer surface.
Class: Supply Chain. Definition: The entity “Supply Chain” describes the supply chain from the topmost level with all possible material flow edges, referring on the FabIDs (master entity)

Class: Supply Chain. Definition: A SUPPLY CHAIN is the network of organizations, resources, activities, and technologies involved in the production and delivery of a product from raw materials to the final customer. Supply chain management issues have become increasingly important to the semiconductor industry due to the global distribution of facilities and its inherent long production time.

Class: Target Costs. Definition: The target costs entity is the final cost of a product or service that must be achieved in order to generate the desired level of sales revenue and income or due to contractual agreements.
Class: Target Revenue. Definition: The target revenue is the amount of income a company wants to generate for the current accounting period.
Class: Target Service Level. Definition: The target service level is a performance indicator expressing the percentage of orders satisfied.

Class: Technology. Definition: A semiconductor technology is a set of equipment, processes, manufacturing techniques and the related methods and procedures to enable the design & production of components, sub-components and modules.
Class: Tempering. Definition: The tempering process is a type of heat treatment applied by the furnace. The process has the effect of toughening by lessing brittleness and reducing internal stresses.

Class: Time Constraints. Definition: As single operations can set the lot to a time-critical state, time constraints can ensure that the operation setting it to an uncritical state is not delayed. Also the other case where certain time has to be spent between two operations can be covered with this master entity. (workflow deswcriptive master entities)

Class: Time Coupling. Definition: Lots of this type are requested by the next machine in the production line in irregular intervals. Special chemical characteristics require the lot being further processed immediately after the furnace operation. Thus, the downstram machines keep capacity free for the resulting time slot. timecoupling can be turned on or off. if it is on all lots are processed no matter how many are waiting and if not they wait.

Class: Tool. Definition: A tool is any pieve of semiconductor fabrication or inspection equipment designed to process wafers. Often used synonymously with equipment in the silicon wafer processing industry.
Class: Wet Etching. Definition: Wet Etching is the process of removing material-etching, through the use of chemical activity.

Class: Work In Progress Station. Definition: Work in Progress (WIP) processing occurs here. WIP refers to the units of production that have been released into the factory, but have not yet been scrapped, have not been sent our for external rework, and have not finished processing through all of the production steps.
Class: Workshop. Definition: The overall organizational working structures within the fabs is described in the entity “Workshop” (master entity)

Class: Agent. Definition: "The Agent class is the class of agents; things that do stuff. A well known sub-class is Person, representing people. Other kinds of agents include Organization and Group.  The Agent class is useful in a few places in FOAF where Person would have been overly specific. For example, the IM chat ID properties such as jabberID are typically associated with people, but sometimes belong to software bots."
Class: Document. Definition: The foaf:Document class represents those things which are, broadly conceived, 'documents'

Class: Person. Definition: The Person class represents people. Something is a Person if it is a person. We don't nitpic about whether they're alive, dead, real, or imaginary. The Person class is a sub-class of the Agent class, since all people are considered 'agents' in FOAF.

Description: If a proper interval T1 is intervalFinishes another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is after the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is coincident with the end of T2.

ObjectProperty: interval finishes (Domain: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#ProperInterval, Range: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#ProperInterval). Description: Si un intervalo propio T1 termina otro intervalo propio T2, entonces del principio de T1 está después del principio de T2, y el final de T1 coincide con el final de T2.

Description: If a proper interval T1 is intervalFinishes another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is after the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is coincident with the end of T2.

ObjectProperty: intervalo termina (Domain: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#ProperInterval, Range: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#ProperInterval). Description: Si un intervalo propio T1 termina otro intervalo propio T2, entonces del principio de T1 está después del principio de T2, y el final de T1 coincide con el final de T2.

ObjectProperty: interval starts (Domain: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#ProperInterval, Range: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#ProperInterval). Description: If a proper interval T1 is intervalStarts another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is coincident with the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is before the end of T2.

ObjectProperty: interval starts (Domain: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#ProperInterval, Range: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#ProperInterval). Description: Si un intervalo propio T1 empieza otro intervalo propio T2, entonces del principio de T1 con el principio de T2, y el final de T1 es anterior al final de T2.

ObjectProperty: intervalo empieza (Domain: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#ProperInterval, Range: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#ProperInterval). Description: If a proper interval T1 is intervalStarts another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is coincident with the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is before the end of T2.

ObjectProperty: intervalo empieza (Domain: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#ProperInterval, Range: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#ProperInterval). ObjectProperty: interval after (Domain: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Proper_Interval, Range: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Proper_Interval). Description: If a proper interval T1 is intervalAfter another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is after the end of T2.

ObjectProperty: interval before (Domain: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Proper_Interval, Range: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Proper_Interval). Description: If a proper interval T1 is intervalBefore another proper interval T2, then the end of T1 is before the beginning of T2.

ObjectProperty: interval contains (Domain: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Proper_Interval, Range: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Proper_Interval). Description: If a proper interval T1 is intervalContains another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is before the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is after the end of T2.

ObjectProperty: interval disjoint (Domain: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Proper_Interval, Range: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Proper_Interval). Description: If a proper interval T1 is intervalDisjoint another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is after the end of T2, or the end of T1 is before the beginning of T2, i.e. the intervals do not overlap in any way, but their ordering relationship is not known.

ObjectProperty: interval during (Domain: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Proper_Interval, Range: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Proper_Interval). ObjectProperty: interval equals (Domain: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Proper_Interval, Range: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Proper_Interval). Description: If a proper interval T1 is intervalEquals another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is coincident with the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is coincident with the end of T2.

ObjectProperty: interval finished by (Domain: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Proper_Interval, Range: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Proper_Interval). Description: If a proper interval T1 is intervalFinishedBy another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is before the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is coincident with the end of T2.

ObjectProperty: interval finishes (Domain: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Proper_Interval, Range: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Proper_Interval). Description: If a proper interval T1 is intervalFinishes another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is after the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is coincident with the end of T2.

ObjectProperty: interval in (Domain: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Proper_Interval, Range: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Proper_Interval). Description: If a proper interval T1 is intervalIn another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is after the beginning of T2 or is coincident with the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is before the end of T2, or is coincident with the end of T2, except that end of T1 may not be coincident with the end of T2 if the beginning of T1 is coincident with the beginning of T2.

ObjectProperty: interval meets (Domain: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Proper_Interval, Range: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Proper_Interval). Description: If a proper interval T1 is intervalMeets another proper interval T2, then the end of T1 is coincident with the beginning of T2.

ObjectProperty: interval met by (Domain: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Proper_Interval, Range: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Proper_Interval). Description: If a proper interval T1 is intervalMetBy another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is coincident with the end of T2.

ObjectProperty: interval overlapped by (Domain: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Proper_Interval, Range: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Proper_Interval). Description: If a proper interval T1 is intervalOverlappedBy another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is after the beginning of T2, the beginning of T1 is before the end of T2, and the end of T1 is after the end of T2.

ObjectProperty: interval overlaps (Domain: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Proper_Interval, Range: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Proper_Interval). Description: If a proper interval T1 is intervalOverlaps another proper interval T2, then the beginning of T1 is before the beginning of T2, the end of T1 is after the beginning of T2, and the end of T1 is before the end of T2.

ObjectProperty: interval started by (Domain: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Proper_Interval, Range: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Proper_Interval). ObjectProperty: interval starts (Domain: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Proper_Interval, Range: http://www.w3.org/2006/time#Proper_Interval). Description: Relation between an Interface Design Description document (of a specific service) and a method of this service. The relation expresses that the IDD document documents the methods of the service the IDD belongs to. With this, a consistency check would be possible: IF a service S has a method M AND the IDD IDD_S is part of the service documentation of S (i.e. IDD_S is the IDD of S) THEN IDD_S should contain a documentation of M.

ObjectProperty: produces (Domain: http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-AH#Software_System, Range: http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-AH#Service). Description: Relation expressing that a software system produces a service. Equivalent names for this relation include: offers, provides, isServiceProducerOf Since Arrowhead uses the pair produce / consume and corresponding service producer / service consumer adressing the relations and the software systems, this ontology uses these names for the relations too. If it is needed, object properties with other names can be added and stated to be equivalent to these ones.

ObjectProperty: refers to (Domain: http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-AH#Documentation_Document, Range: http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-AH#Documentation_Document). Description: describes the relation between two documentation documents that one document refers to another document. To our best knowledge, the following relations hold between different types of documentation documents: - an IDD refers to exactly one SD. - an SD is referred to by one or more IDD (each stating a way of implementing the service with a specific technolopgy (Source: Arrowhead Framework Definitions V2.4)) - an IDD refers to at most one CP (if it not refers to a CP, then the IDD contains all CP information by itself) - an IDD refers to n SP, 0 <= n (if it not refers to a SP, then the IDD contains all SP information by itself) - a SySD refers to one or more IDDs (that is, a system produces one or more services). - a SySDD refers to one or more SySD's. (Remark HB: I don't understand this. How can one concrete white box description of a system fulfill (support / implement) different black box descriptions of systems? The other way around seems to be possible as between SDs and IDDs). - an SoSD refers to n SySD's. - an SoSDD refers to n SoSD's. - an SoSDD refers to n SySD's. - an SoSDD refers to n SySDDs.

ObjectProperty: refers to CP (Domain: http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-AH#Interface_Design_Description_IDD, Range: http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-AH#Communication_Profile_CP). Description: an Interface Design Description (IDD) can refer to a Communication Profile (CP). No other documentation document can refer to a CP. Hence the domain of this object property is the class of IDDs. An IDD can refer to a CP, but this is not mandatory. CPs are intended to be used in cases in which several services use the same CP. Then the CP information should be extracted to an CP document and the IDDs of all services that use this CP shall refer to this CP. If the CP is unique for a specific service, the CP information can directly be included in the IDD. If the IDD refers to a CP, this must be a unique reference. That is, one IDD must not refer to different CPs. Hence this object property is functional. (If the service could be implemented using different communication technologies, each implementation would need an own IDD!!).

ObjectProperty: refers to SP (Domain: http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-AH#Interface_Design_Description_IDD, Range: http://www.w3id.org/ecsel-dr-AH#Semantic_Profile_SP). Description: an Interface Design Description (IDD) can refer to a Semantic Profile (SP). No other documentation document can refer to a SP. Hence the domain of this object property is the class of IDDs. An IDD can refer to a SP, but this is not mandatory. SPs are intended to be used in cases in which several services use the same SP. Then the SCP information should be extracted to an SP document and the IDDs of all services that use this SP shall refer to this SP. If the SP is unique for a specific service, the SP information can directly be included in the IDD. References to SPs are not necessarily unique for an IDD. That is, different methods of the service documented by the IDD can use different Semantic Profiles.

Typical criteria are maximization, minimization, i.e. if an optimization problem is considered, or larger or smaller than a prescribed value of the certain performance measure, a so-called target, i.e. if a satisfaction problem is solved.
